21
00:01:20,881 --> 00:01:24,216
 <i> OUR FIRST STORY INVESTIGATES</i>  
      <i> A MARITIME MYSTERY</i>       

22
00:01:24,285 --> 00:01:28,120
         <i> WASHED UP ON</i>          
       <i> AN OREGON BEACH.</i>        

23
00:01:31,192 --> 00:01:34,893
    <i> 1846: TENSIONS BETWEEN</i>     
     <i> THE U.S. AND BRITAIN</i>      

24
00:01:34,962 --> 00:01:36,895
       <i> ARE APPROACHING</i>         
       <i> A BOILING POINT.</i>        

25
00:01:36,964 --> 00:01:38,764
     <i> ALL EYES ARE FOCUSED</i>      

26
00:01:38,833 --> 00:01:40,899
    <i> ON THE DISPUTED BORDER</i>     
       <i> BETWEEN THE U.S.</i>        

27
00:01:40,968 --> 00:01:44,436
   <i> AND THE BRITISH COLONIAL</i>    
     <i> TERRITORY OF CANADA.</i>      

28
00:01:44,505 --> 00:01:46,838
    <i> AT STAKE IS OWNERSHIP</i>      
    <i> OF THE ENORMOUS RICHES</i>     

29
00:01:46,907 --> 00:01:51,577
 <i> OF SOME 300,000 SQUARE MILES</i>  
  <i> OF THE PACIFIC NORTHWEST.</i>    

30
00:01:51,645 --> 00:01:53,612
        <i> THE U.S. NEEDS</i>         
        <i> RECONNAISSANCE</i>         

31
00:01:53,681 --> 00:01:56,114
        <i> AND DISPATCHES</i>         
    <i> AN ARMED NAVAL VESSEL,</i>     

32
00:01:56,183 --> 00:01:58,383
        <i> THE</i> USS SHARK.         

33
00:01:58,452 --> 00:02:00,786
     <i> BUT THAT SEPTEMBER,</i>       
      <i> DISASTER STRIKES.</i>        

34
00:02:00,854 --> 00:02:02,888
       <i> THE</i> SHARK<i> WRECKS</i>        
          <i> AND SINKS</i>            

35
00:02:02,957 --> 00:02:06,325
   <i> AT THE TREACHEROUS MOUTH</i>    
    <i> OF THE COLUMBIA RIVER.</i>     

36
00:02:06,393 --> 00:02:08,794
     <i> MORE THAN A CENTURY</i>       
      <i> AND A HALF LATER,</i>        

37
00:02:08,862 --> 00:02:10,963
         <i> 14-YEAR-OLD</i>           
       <i> MIRANDA PETRONE</i>         

38
00:02:11,031 --> 00:02:13,999
    <i> FROM TUALATIN, OREGON,</i>     
  <i> THINKS SHE MAY HAVE FOUND</i>    

39
00:02:14,068 --> 00:02:16,235
       <i> A PIECE OF THIS</i>         
        <i> HISTORIC SHIP.</i>         

40
00:02:16,303 --> 00:02:18,637
  ME AND MY DAD WERE WALKING    
       ALONG THE BEACH,         

41
00:02:18,706 --> 00:02:20,739
   AND I SAW THIS BIG THING     
          WITH RUST,            

42
00:02:20,808 --> 00:02:22,574
         AND I'M LIKE,          
    "HEY, DAD, COME HERE."      

43
00:02:22,643 --> 00:02:23,709
HI.                             

44
00:02:23,777 --> 00:02:26,011
               I'M GWEN WRIGHT, 
               NICE TO MEET YOU.

45
00:02:26,080 --> 00:02:28,246
 SO I HEAR YOU FOUND SOMETHING  
 PRETTY INTERESTING AROUND HERE.

46
00:02:28,315 --> 00:02:29,615
YEAH, I DID.                    

47
00:02:29,683 --> 00:02:31,483
                    WHAT WAS IT?
I FOUND A CANNON.               

48
00:02:31,552 --> 00:02:33,085
               NOW, ARE YOU SURE
               IT WAS A CANNON? 

49
00:02:33,153 --> 00:02:34,620
WELL, NOT AT FIRST.             

50
00:02:34,688 --> 00:02:36,455
ME AND MY DAD WERE WALKING      
ALONG THE BEACH                 

51
00:02:36,523 --> 00:02:39,024
AND THERE WAS THIS              
BIG BLACK ROCKY THING,          

52
00:02:39,093 --> 00:02:41,393
SO I WENT UP A LITTLE CLOSER    
AND EVENTUALLY SAW RUST.        

53
00:02:41,462 --> 00:02:43,996
I THOUGHT, "ROCKS AREN'T        
SUPPOSED TO HAVE RUST,"         

54
00:02:44,064 --> 00:02:45,430
AND SO I CALLED                 
MY DAD OVER.                    

55
00:02:45,499 --> 00:02:46,932
HE CAME AND                     
CHECKED IT OUT.                 

56
00:02:47,001 --> 00:02:48,767
HE WAS LIKE, "HUH,              
MAYBE IT'S A CANNON."           

57
00:02:48,836 --> 00:02:51,003
HE WAS JUST JOKING, THOUGH,     
BUT I STILL WENT OUT THERE,     

58
00:02:51,071 --> 00:02:52,971
AND IT WAS, SO...               

59
00:02:53,040 --> 00:02:54,906
       NOW, I'M HOPING THOSE ARE
       SOME PICTURES YOU TOOK.  

60
00:02:54,975 --> 00:02:56,875
                  IS THAT RIGHT?
YES.                            

61
00:02:56,944 --> 00:02:58,310
                 SO THIS IS YOU.

62
00:02:58,379 --> 00:02:59,778
          ARE THESE YOUR SISTERS
          OR FRIENDS?           

63
00:02:59,847 --> 00:03:02,247
WELL, THAT ONE'S MY SISTER      
AND THAT ONE'S MY FRIEND.       

64
00:03:02,316 --> 00:03:05,117
  WHAT DID YOU NOTICE, ACTUALLY,
  WAS IT THIS RUST HERE?        

65
00:03:05,185 --> 00:03:07,919
YEAH, I WALKED UP CLOSER        
AND SAW THERE WAS RUST.         

66
00:03:07,988 --> 00:03:10,756
AND THEN THIS FRIEND OF OURS    
FOUND THE SECOND ONE.           

67
00:03:10,824 --> 00:03:13,692
    <i> MIRANDA'S FRIEND MADE</i>      
       <i> A SIMILAR FIND,</i>         

68
00:03:13,761 --> 00:03:16,595
         <i> ANOTHER BIG</i>           
    <i> STONE-COVERED OBJECT.</i>      

69
00:03:16,663 --> 00:03:18,130
       WAS IT IN THE SAME PLACE?

70
00:03:18,198 --> 00:03:20,665
UM, NO, IT WAS PROBABLY         
A LITTLE BIT FARTHER OUT.       

71
00:03:20,734 --> 00:03:25,070
<i> MIRANDA'S DISCOVERY GENERATED</i>  
  <i> A LOT OF LOCAL EXCITEMENT.</i>   

72
00:03:25,139 --> 00:03:27,406
     <i> THE MEDIA SPECULATED</i>      
     <i> SHE'D FOUND A RELIC</i>       

73
00:03:27,474 --> 00:03:31,343
 <i> FROM THE SHIPWRECK OF AN OLD</i>  
<i> NAVY VESSEL CALLED THE</i> SHARK.  

74
00:03:31,412 --> 00:03:33,512
IT WAS MADE IN 1821,            

75
00:03:33,580 --> 00:03:35,947
AND IT CRASHED IN 1846          
AROUND THIS AREA.               

76
00:03:36,016 --> 00:03:37,716
           WHAT DID YOU DO NEXT?

77
00:03:37,785 --> 00:03:39,618
MY DAD, HE LOOKED               
AT THIS BOOK,                   

78
00:03:39,686 --> 00:03:41,653
AND IT SHOWED PICTURES          
OF THE<i> SHARK,</i>                   

79
00:03:41,722 --> 00:03:43,355
KIND OF LOOKED AT THEM,         
WE WERE LIKE,                   

80
00:03:43,424 --> 00:03:45,190
"OKAY, WELL, THIS HAS           
SOME SIMILARITIES."             

81
00:03:45,259 --> 00:03:47,159
      <i> MIRANDA'S RESEARCH</i>       
          <i> INDICATED</i>            

82
00:03:47,227 --> 00:03:49,428
     <i> THAT THE</i> SHARK<i> SANK</i>       
    <i> IN THE COLUMBIA RIVER</i>      

83
00:03:49,496 --> 00:03:52,431
        <i> 60 TO 75 MILES</i>         
        <i> NORTH OF HERE</i>          

84
00:03:52,499 --> 00:03:55,133
    <i> AND THAT SOME WRECKAGE</i>     
   <i> COULD HAVE DRIFTED SOUTH</i>    

85
00:03:55,202 --> 00:03:56,835
        <i> TO THIS BEACH.</i>         

86
00:03:56,904 --> 00:03:59,504
  CAN YOU TELL ME EXACTLY WHAT  
  YOU'D LIKE FOR ME TO FIND OUT?

87
00:03:59,573 --> 00:04:01,640
I'D LIKE TO FIND OUT            
IF IT REALLY IS A CANNON        

88
00:04:01,708 --> 00:04:04,042
AND IF IT REALLY DID            
COME FROM THE<i> SHARK.</i>            

89
00:04:04,111 --> 00:04:05,610
        I'LL SEE WHAT I CAN FIND
        FOR YOU, OKAY?          

90
00:04:05,679 --> 00:04:07,579
    OKAY.                       

91
00:04:07,648 --> 00:04:10,415
  <i> WHATEVER IT IS SHE'S FOUND</i>   
    <i> IS NOW BEING PROTECTED</i>     

92
00:04:10,484 --> 00:04:13,051
     <i> BY THE OREGON PARKS</i>       
  <i> AND RECREATION DEPARTMENT</i>    

93
00:04:13,120 --> 00:04:15,353
        <i> AT NEHALEM BAY</i>         
         <i> STATE PARK.</i>           

94
00:04:15,422 --> 00:04:17,022
        HI, ARE YOU CHRIS HAVEL?
I AM.                           

95
00:04:17,090 --> 00:04:19,224
            GWEN WRIGHT,        
            SO NICE TO MEET YOU.

96
00:04:19,293 --> 00:04:21,493
        <i> CHRIS HAVEL IS</i>         
   <i> THE PROJECT COORDINATOR</i>     

97
00:04:21,562 --> 00:04:23,962
     <i> FOR THE DEPARTMENT'S</i>      
     <i> CANNON CONSERVATION.</i>      

98
00:04:24,031 --> 00:04:26,531
              LET'S TAKE A LOOK.
OH, MY.                         

99
00:04:26,600 --> 00:04:29,201
IT'S ACTUALLY BEAUTIFUL,        
ALL THESE COLORS.               

100
00:04:29,269 --> 00:04:32,471
WELL, I CAN SEE THAT THIS ONE   
CERTAINLY LOOKS LIKE A CANNON,  

101
00:04:32,539 --> 00:04:34,372
ALTHOUGH THE OTHER ONE,         
NOT AT ALL.                     

102
00:04:34,441 --> 00:04:37,042
           SO WHAT IS THIS STUFF
           THAT'S ALL OVER IT   

103
00:04:37,110 --> 00:04:39,644
           BEYOND THE ROCKS     
           AND STONES I CAN SEE?

104
00:04:39,713 --> 00:04:41,580
WELL, THESE ARE CONCRETIONS.    

105
00:04:41,648 --> 00:04:43,748
THIS IS A NATURAL FORM          
OF CONCRETE                     

106
00:04:43,817 --> 00:04:46,585
THAT FORMS AROUND ANYTHING      
THAT'S LEFT ON THE OCEAN SHORE  

107
00:04:46,653 --> 00:04:49,487
IN CONTACT WITH THE SAND        
FOR A LONG PERIOD OF TIME.      

108
00:04:49,556 --> 00:04:52,858
    DOES THIS KIND OF CONCRETION
    GIVE YOU ANY IDEA ABOUT AGE?

109
00:04:52,926 --> 00:04:56,228
  IT'S DIFFICULT TO TELL THE AGE
  JUST BASED ON THE CONCRETION. 

110
00:04:56,296 --> 00:04:59,664
  THE KIND OF CHEMICALS THAT ARE
  ON THE BEACH, THE WEATHERING, 

111
00:04:59,733 --> 00:05:02,234
        HOW MUCH WATER IS THERE,
        THE SALINITY,           

112
00:05:02,302 --> 00:05:04,970
          ALL OF THESE THINGS   
          CAN AFFECT HOW QUICKLY

113
00:05:05,038 --> 00:05:06,738
                 THE CONCRETIONS
                 BUILD UP.      

114
00:05:06,807 --> 00:05:08,840
          <i> CHRIS SAYS</i>           
     <i> MIRANDA'S DISCOVERY</i>       

115
00:05:08,909 --> 00:05:12,077
  <i> HAS THE DEPARTMENT EXCITED</i>   
    <i> BECAUSE 100 YEARS AGO,</i>     

116
00:05:12,145 --> 00:05:16,081
<i> ANOTHER CANNON, ALSO PRESUMED</i>  
  <i> TO BE FROM THE</i> USS SHARK,    

117
00:05:16,149 --> 00:05:19,184
      <i> WAS RETRIEVED FROM</i>       
     <i> THE VERY SAME BEACH.</i>      

118
00:05:19,253 --> 00:05:21,219
        I'VE GOT A DRAWING HERE.

119
00:05:21,288 --> 00:05:24,189
<i> CHRIS COMPARES THE SOAKING MASS</i>
     <i> OF SEDIMENT AND RUST</i>      

120
00:05:24,258 --> 00:05:27,559
      <i> TO A DIAGRAM OF A </i>       
      SHARK-ERA<i> CARRONADE,</i>      

121
00:05:27,628 --> 00:05:31,463
<i> OR SHORT-BARRELED CANNON, THAT</i> 
 <i> COULD BE HIDDEN BENEATH IT.</i>   

122
00:05:31,531 --> 00:05:34,299
   <i> BUT IF I'M TO DETERMINE</i>     
   <i> WHETHER MIRANDA'S CANNON</i>    

123
00:05:34,368 --> 00:05:35,967
    <i> IS FROM THE</i> USS SHARK,     

124
00:05:36,036 --> 00:05:38,303
      <i> I'LL NEED TO LEARN</i>       
  <i> ALL I CAN ABOUT THE SHIP,</i>    

125
00:05:38,372 --> 00:05:41,539
        <i> STARTING WITH</i>          
      <i> ITS FINAL VOYAGE.</i>        

126
00:05:41,608 --> 00:05:43,508
        <i> I'M RETRACING</i>          
      <i> THE</i> SHARK'S<i> ROUTE</i>        

127
00:05:43,577 --> 00:05:45,844
    <i> UP THE COLUMBIA RIVER</i>      
      <i> TO FORT VANCOUVER,</i>       

128
00:05:45,912 --> 00:05:48,179
   <i> WHERE THE SHIP ANCHORED</i>     
    <i> WHEN IT FIRST ARRIVED</i>      

129
00:05:48,248 --> 00:05:50,181
  <i> IN THE PACIFIC NORTHWEST.</i>    

130
00:05:50,250 --> 00:05:52,284
       <i> THE FORT, NOW IN</i>        
      <i> WASHINGTON STATE,</i>        

131
00:05:52,352 --> 00:05:54,586
     <i> THEN OPERATED UNDER</i>       
      <i> AN ENGLISH CHARTER</i>       

132
00:05:54,655 --> 00:05:56,855
       <i> AND BELONGED TO</i>         
  <i> THE HUDSON'S BAY COMPANY,</i>    

133
00:05:56,923 --> 00:05:59,758
    <i> THE FIRST CORPORATION</i>      
      <i> IN NORTH AMERICA.</i>        

134
00:05:59,826 --> 00:06:01,593
          <i> GREG SHINE</i>           
       <i> IS CHIEF RANGER.</i>        

135
00:06:01,662 --> 00:06:03,094
      WELCOME TO FORT VANCOUVER.

136
00:06:03,163 --> 00:06:04,796
                 HERE'S AN IMAGE
                 OF THE<i> SHARK.</i>  

137
00:06:04,865 --> 00:06:08,600
   THE<i> SHARK</i> WAS A SCHOONER,    
   AND SHE WAS LAUNCHED IN 1821.

138
00:06:08,669 --> 00:06:10,769
              AND A FORE-AND-AFT
              RIGGED SCHOONER,  

139
00:06:10,837 --> 00:06:13,705
    WHICH MEANT IT HAD TWO MASTS
    HERE SLIGHTLY RAKED BACK.   

140
00:06:13,774 --> 00:06:15,373
        <i> THE</i> SHARK<i> WAS</i>          
         <i> WELL-ARMED,</i>           

141
00:06:15,442 --> 00:06:17,208
        <i> HAVING POLICED</i>         
     <i> WEST AFRICAN WATERS</i>       

142
00:06:17,277 --> 00:06:18,877
   <i> AGAINST THE SLAVE TRADE,</i>    

143
00:06:18,945 --> 00:06:22,280
<i> SAFELY CONDUCTED FREED SLAVES</i>  
  <i> TO NEWLY FOUNDED LIBERIA,</i>    

144
00:06:22,349 --> 00:06:24,382
        <i> AND PROTECTED</i>          
      <i> AMERICAN MERCHANTS</i>       

145
00:06:24,451 --> 00:06:26,317
       <i> AGAINST PIRATES</i>         
      <i> IN THE CARIBBEAN.</i>        

146
00:06:26,386 --> 00:06:30,121
BUT I CAN'T SEE ANY CANNONS     
IN THIS PICTURE.                

147
00:06:30,190 --> 00:06:32,524
DO YOU KNOW HOW MANY            
SHE WAS CARRYING?               

148
00:06:32,592 --> 00:06:34,926
             YES, THE<i> SHARK</i>     
              HAD TEN CARRONADES

149
00:06:34,995 --> 00:06:39,197
    AND TWO LONG GUNS, AND THESE
    LITTLE OPEN AREAS HERE      

150
00:06:39,266 --> 00:06:41,533
              WERE CANNON PORTS.

151
00:06:41,601 --> 00:06:44,869
    <i> THIS EXPERIENCED SHIP</i>      
      <i> WAS CHOSEN TO SAIL</i>       

152
00:06:44,938 --> 00:06:48,339
  <i> FOR THE PACIFIC NORTHWEST</i>    
           <i> IN 1846.</i>            

153
00:06:48,408 --> 00:06:51,309
  <i> AS THE U.S. BORDER DISPUTE</i>   
  <i> WITH BRITAIN INTENSIFIED,</i>    

154
00:06:51,378 --> 00:06:54,012
    <i> THE</i> SHARK'S<i> COMMANDER,</i>     
      <i> LT. NEIL HOWISON,</i>        

155
00:06:54,081 --> 00:06:56,281
        <i> WAS INSTRUCTED</i>         
      <i> TO RALLY AMERICANS</i>       

156
00:06:56,349 --> 00:06:58,149
        <i> WITH A DISPLAY</i>         
         <i> OF THE FLAG,</i>          

157
00:06:58,218 --> 00:07:00,151
            <i> SURVEY</i>             
    <i> THE OREGON TERRITORY,</i>      

158
00:07:00,220 --> 00:07:02,387
    <i> AND TALK WITH BRITISH</i>      
  <i> AND AMERICAN HOMESTEADERS</i>    

159
00:07:02,456 --> 00:07:03,922
        <i> LIVING THERE.</i>          

160
00:07:03,990 --> 00:07:05,623
                 HIS ORDERS WERE
                 VERY DIRECT:   

161
00:07:05,692 --> 00:07:07,892
       HE WAS TO COME IN TO     
       OBTAIN THEIR DISPOSITION,

162
00:07:07,961 --> 00:07:10,762
   WHETHER IT WAS FOR THE UNITED
   STATES OR FOR GREAT BRITAIN, 

163
00:07:10,831 --> 00:07:13,298
             AND ALSO TO REPORT 
             ON THE AGRICULTURE,

164
00:07:13,366 --> 00:07:15,033
       THE COMMERCE OF THE AREA,

165
00:07:15,102 --> 00:07:18,069
     AND GIVE A GENERAL OVERVIEW
     OF THE OREGON COUNTRY.     

166
00:07:18,138 --> 00:07:19,737
    <i> HOWISON KNEW A MISSTEP</i>     

167
00:07:19,806 --> 00:07:22,640
 <i> COULD EASILY IGNITE TENSIONS</i>  
         <i> IN THE AREA.</i>          

168
00:07:22,709 --> 00:07:24,275
       <i> PRESIDENT POLK'S</i>        
       <i> DEMOCRATIC PARTY</i>        

169
00:07:24,344 --> 00:07:26,511
  <i> WAS PUSHING TO LEGITIMIZE</i>    
     <i> AMERICAN SETTLEMENTS</i>      

170
00:07:26,580 --> 00:07:28,179
    <i> ACROSS THE CONTINENT.</i>      

171
00:07:28,248 --> 00:07:31,082
     <i> ONLY A YEAR EARLIER,</i>      
           <i> IN 1845,</i>            

172
00:07:31,151 --> 00:07:34,185
    <i> THIS DRIVE WAS DUBBED</i>      
     <i> "MANIFEST DESTINY,"</i>       

173
00:07:34,254 --> 00:07:35,920
       <i> IMPLYING THAT IT</i>        
        <i> WAS GOD'S WILL</i>         

174
00:07:35,989 --> 00:07:39,591
    <i> FOR THE UNITED STATES</i>      
<i> TO EXPAND ACROSS THE CONTINENT</i> 

175
00:07:39,659 --> 00:07:43,361
     <i> WEST TO THE PACIFIC,</i>      
  <i> SOUTH INTO LATIN AMERICA,</i>    

176
00:07:43,430 --> 00:07:46,464
        <i> AND NORTH INTO</i>         
       <i> BRITISH CANADA.</i>         

177
00:07:46,533 --> 00:07:50,134
  <i> THIS BELIEF HELPED INFLAME</i>   
  <i> THE POLITICAL RALLYING CRY</i>   

178
00:07:50,203 --> 00:07:52,270
     <i> OF "54-40 OR FIGHT,"</i>      

179
00:07:52,339 --> 00:07:54,772
       <i> A CALL TO EXTEND</i>        
       <i> AMERICA'S REACH</i>         

180
00:07:54,841 --> 00:07:56,841
    <i> THROUGH BRITISH CANADA</i>     
         <i> ALL THE WAY</i>           

181
00:07:56,910 --> 00:08:00,445
    <i> TO LATITUDE 54 DEGREES</i>     
       <i> AND 40 MINUTES.</i>         

182
00:08:00,514 --> 00:08:03,615
  <i> THE OREGON SETTLERS NEEDED</i>   
    <i> LITTLE ENCOURAGEMENT.</i>      

183
00:08:03,683 --> 00:08:05,917
          THERE WERE CERTAINLY  
          SOME AMERICAN SETTLERS

184
00:08:05,986 --> 00:08:08,486
     THAT WERE HERE THAT WERE   
     CROSSING THE COLUMBIA RIVER

185
00:08:08,555 --> 00:08:10,421
                   AND BEGINNING
                   TO HOMESTEAD,

186
00:08:10,490 --> 00:08:12,757
    OR, IN THE EYES             
    OF THE HUDSON'S BAY COMPANY,

187
00:08:12,826 --> 00:08:15,360
   JUMPED LAND CLAIMS           
   THAT THE HUDSON'S BAY COMPANY

188
00:08:15,428 --> 00:08:16,794
                HAD ESTABLISHED.

189
00:08:16,863 --> 00:08:19,497
WHAT WAS THE BRITISH RESPONSE   
TO THE<i> SHARK</i> ARRIVING?          

190
00:08:19,566 --> 00:08:22,033
        THE HUDSON'S BAY COMPANY
        WELCOMED THE<i> SHARK</i>      

191
00:08:22,102 --> 00:08:24,702
   AND LT. HOWISON              
   AND WELCOMED AN AMERICAN SHIP

192
00:08:24,771 --> 00:08:27,071
         INTO THE COLUMBIA RIVER
         BECAUSE THEY PROVIDED  

193
00:08:27,140 --> 00:08:28,740
             SOME LAW AND ORDER,
             REALLY,            

194
00:08:28,808 --> 00:08:30,708
     TO AN AREA THAT DIDN'T HAVE
     MUCH LAW AND ORDER.        

195
00:08:30,777 --> 00:08:33,077
        <i> WITH THE LAND</i>          
  <i> AND TEMPERAMENT SURVEYED,</i>    

196
00:08:33,146 --> 00:08:35,380
       <i> HOWISON SET SAIL</i>        
      <i> FOR SAN FRANCISCO</i>        

197
00:08:35,448 --> 00:08:36,981
     <i> TO FILE HIS REPORT.</i>       

198
00:08:37,050 --> 00:08:38,449
                 WHEN THEY LEFT 
                 FORT VANCOUVER,

199
00:08:38,518 --> 00:08:40,018
               THEY WERE ALREADY
               BEHIND SCHEDULE. 

200
00:08:40,086 --> 00:08:41,686
               THE WINTER CAN BE
               VERY FEROCIOUS,  

201
00:08:41,755 --> 00:08:43,488
       AND ESPECIALLY           
       AT THE MOUTH OF THE RIVER

202
00:08:43,556 --> 00:08:45,657
    NEAR THE COLUMBIA RIVER BAR.

203
00:08:45,725 --> 00:08:48,393
         <i> AS THE</i> SHARK          
    <i> HEADED FOR OPEN SEAS,</i>      

204
00:08:48,461 --> 00:08:50,495
        <i> IT WRECKED ON</i>          
     <i> AN UNCHARTED SANDBAR</i>      

205
00:08:50,563 --> 00:08:52,397
         <i> AT THE MOUTH</i>          
       <i> OF THE COLUMBIA.</i>        

206
00:08:52,465 --> 00:08:56,000
   LUCKILY, ALL OF THE PERSONNEL
   WERE ABLE TO SURVIVE.        

207
00:08:56,069 --> 00:08:59,570
   <i> GREG SHOWS ME HOWISON'S</i>     
 <i> REPORT TO THE U.S. CONGRESS.</i>  

208
00:08:59,639 --> 00:09:03,608
<i> ONE PASSAGE MAY RELATE DIRECTLY</i>
   <i> TO MIRANDA'S DISCOVERY.</i>     

209
00:09:03,677 --> 00:09:06,210
   <i> IT SAYS HOWISON IS EAGER</i>    
          <i> TO RECOVER</i>           

210
00:09:06,279 --> 00:09:08,446
          <i> THE SHIP'S</i>           
        <i> LOST WEAPONS.</i>          

211
00:09:08,515 --> 00:09:11,015
"RECEIVING INFORMATIONS         
THAT PART OF THE HULL           

212
00:09:11,084 --> 00:09:13,551
"WITH GUNS UPON IT              
HAD COME ASHORE,                

213
00:09:13,620 --> 00:09:16,387
"I SENT MIDSHIPMAN SIMES,       
AN ENTERPRISING YOUTH,          

214
00:09:16,456 --> 00:09:17,922
TO VISIT THE SPOT."             

215
00:09:17,991 --> 00:09:19,590
         <i> IN THE WATER</i>          
     <i> JUST OFF THE BEACH,</i>       

216
00:09:19,659 --> 00:09:21,559
         <i> SIMES FOUND</i>           
   <i> A BROKEN SECTION OF DECK</i>    

217
00:09:21,628 --> 00:09:24,729
  <i> WITH THREE OF THE</i> SHARK'S    
     <i> ONE-TON CARRONADES.</i>       

218
00:09:24,798 --> 00:09:28,232
"HE SUCCEEDED IN GETTING ONE    
ABOVE THE HIGH-WATER MARK,      

219
00:09:28,301 --> 00:09:30,201
"BUT THE OTHER TWO              
WERE INACCESSIBLE               

220
00:09:30,270 --> 00:09:32,637
ON ACCOUNT OF THE SURF."        

221
00:09:32,706 --> 00:09:34,706
          <i> GREG SAYS</i>            
    <i> THE RESCUED CARRONADE</i>      

222
00:09:34,774 --> 00:09:36,441
         <i> WAS DRAGGED</i>           
       <i> TOWARD THE SHORE</i>        

223
00:09:36,509 --> 00:09:38,409
   <i> BUT HAD TO BE ABANDONED.</i>    

224
00:09:38,478 --> 00:09:41,346
 <i> IN 1898, IT WAS REDISCOVERED</i>  
        <i> AFTER A STORM</i>          

225
00:09:41,414 --> 00:09:43,348
    <i> AND IS NOW ON EXHIBIT</i>      

226
00:09:43,416 --> 00:09:46,718
     <i> AT THE CANNON BEACH</i>       
  <i> HISTORICAL SOCIETY MUSEUM.</i>   

227
00:09:46,786 --> 00:09:48,986
     <i> DID MIRANDA DISCOVER</i>      
        <i> ONE OF THE TWO</i>         

228
00:09:49,055 --> 00:10:01,165
      <i> LEFT IN THE SURF?</i>        

229
00:10:01,234 --> 00:10:03,034
EOLOGIST                        
        <i> DENNIS GRIFFIN</i>         

230
00:10:03,103 --> 00:10:06,170
   <i> SAYS THE COLUMBIA RIVER</i>     
  <i> WAS A NOTORIOUS GRAVEYARD</i>    

231
00:10:06,239 --> 00:10:09,140
    <i> FOR HUNDREDS OF SHIPS,</i>     
     <i> NOT JUST THE</i> SHARK.       

232
00:10:09,209 --> 00:10:12,543
WHAT WE SEE TODAY IS A SMALL    
GLIMPSE OF WHAT IT ONCE WAS.    

233
00:10:12,612 --> 00:10:14,545
IT WAS THE MIGHTY COLUMBIA      
BEFORE ALL THE DAMS.            

234
00:10:14,614 --> 00:10:16,914
BUT THE MOUTH OF THE COLUMBIA   
WAS A VERY WICKED PLACE.        

235
00:10:16,983 --> 00:10:19,450
YOU HAD TIDES COMING UP THERE   
OR STORMS COMING UP THERE       

236
00:10:19,519 --> 00:10:21,486
FROM 35 TO 50 FEET WAVES        
TO CRASH.                       

237
00:10:21,554 --> 00:10:23,421
               FIFTY FEET WAVES!
HUGE WAVES.                     

238
00:10:23,490 --> 00:10:25,389
THEY CALL THIS THE              
GRAVEYARD OF THE PACIFIC.       

239
00:10:25,458 --> 00:10:28,626
    <i> THE MOUTH OF THE RIVER</i>     
  <i> WAS KNOWN TO BE DANGEROUS,</i>   

240
00:10:28,695 --> 00:10:31,829
<i> BUT DENNIS SAYS IF YOU WANTED</i>  
<i> A PIECE OF THE REGION'S WEALTH,</i>

241
00:10:31,898 --> 00:10:34,499
        <i> YOU HAD TO RUN</i>         
   <i> THE COLUMBIA'S GAUNTLET.</i>    

242
00:10:34,567 --> 00:10:36,868
YOU HAD THE HUDSON'S BAY COMPANY
IN CANADA                       

243
00:10:36,936 --> 00:10:38,469
COMING ACROSS FOR FURS.         

244
00:10:38,538 --> 00:10:40,104
LOTS AND LOTS                   
OF SALMON.                      

245
00:10:40,173 --> 00:10:42,573
SAN FRANCISCO AND THE           
BIG CITIES, THEY NEEDED WOOD.   

246
00:10:42,642 --> 00:10:45,109
PEOPLE CAME UP THE COAST,       
FOUND LOTS OF TREES.            

247
00:10:45,178 --> 00:10:49,280
 <i> ALL THAT SHIP TRAFFIC MEANT</i>   
<i> A LOT OF WRECKS OVER THE YEARS.</i>

248
00:10:49,349 --> 00:10:53,384
OF THE 308 I KNOW, I HAVE 104   
THAT I THINK WERE WRECKED       

249
00:10:53,453 --> 00:10:55,520
EITHER AT THE MOUTH             
OF THE COLUMBIA                 

250
00:10:55,588 --> 00:10:57,488
AND DOWN TO ARCH CAPE,          
IN THAT AREA.                   

251
00:10:57,557 --> 00:10:59,757
NOW, OF THOSE 104,              
WE HAVE TO NARROW IT DOWN,      

252
00:10:59,826 --> 00:11:01,292
WHICH ONES CARRIED CANNON,      

253
00:11:01,361 --> 00:11:03,194
AND WE DON'T KNOW THAT,         
AND THAT'S A BIG IMPORTANT PART.

254
00:11:03,263 --> 00:11:04,729
               WHAT DO YOU THINK
               ARE THE ODDS     

255
00:11:04,797 --> 00:11:06,931
        THAT THE CANNONS WE HAVE
        ARE FROM THE<i> SHARK?</i>     

256
00:11:07,000 --> 00:11:08,599
EVERYONE WANTS TO SAY           
IT'S THE<i> SHARK.</i>                 

257
00:11:08,668 --> 00:11:09,800
                    I KNOW.     

258
00:11:09,869 --> 00:11:11,836
AND I'D LIKE TO THINK           
OF IT BEING THE<i> SHARK,</i>          

259
00:11:11,905 --> 00:11:13,738
BUT YOU DON'T KNOW.             

260
00:11:13,806 --> 00:11:16,407
<i> DENNIS SUGGESTS THE RECOVERED</i>  
        SHARK<i> CARRONADE</i>         

261
00:11:16,476 --> 00:11:19,710
      <i> COULD HELP RESOLVE</i>       
         <i> OUR MYSTERY.</i>          

262
00:11:19,779 --> 00:11:23,147
  <i> I'M MEETING COLUMBIA RIVER</i>   
   <i> MARITIME MUSEUM CURATOR</i>     

263
00:11:23,216 --> 00:11:25,650
        <i> DAVID PEARSON</i>          
      <i> FOR A CLOSER LOOK.</i>       

264
00:11:25,718 --> 00:11:28,686
SO THIS IS IT, THE CANNON       
THAT WAS FOUND IN 1898?         

265
00:11:28,755 --> 00:11:31,289
              THIS IS IT, RIGHT,
              JANUARY OF 1898.  

266
00:11:31,357 --> 00:11:34,191
  <i> DAVE SAYS THIS CANNON WAS</i>    
 <i> RECOVERED ON THE SAME BEACH,</i>  

267
00:11:34,260 --> 00:11:38,129
  <i> ABOUT 200 FEET FROM WHERE</i>    
 <i> MIRANDA MADE HER DISCOVERY.</i>   

268
00:11:38,197 --> 00:11:40,131
WAS THIS THE ORIGINAL BASE,     
BY THE WAY?                     

269
00:11:40,199 --> 00:11:42,400
 THIS ONE THAT WE'RE LOOKING AT 
 HERE IS ACTUALLY A REPRODUCTION

270
00:11:42,468 --> 00:11:44,302
            FROM NAVAL DRAWINGS 
            THAT ARE WELL KNOWN.

271
00:11:44,370 --> 00:11:46,737
    <i> IF MIRANDA'S DISCOVERY</i>     
     <i> HAS A SIMILAR BASE,</i>       

272
00:11:46,806 --> 00:11:48,806
      <i> THAT WOULD CONFIRM</i>       
       <i> IT'S A CARRONADE</i>        

273
00:11:48,875 --> 00:11:51,909
     <i> FROM THE RIGHT ERA,</i>       
<i> BUT NOT NECESSARILY THE</i> SHARK  

274
00:11:51,978 --> 00:11:54,245
  <i> OR EVEN AN AMERICAN SHIP.</i>    

275
00:11:54,314 --> 00:11:57,815
  <i> THE CARRONADE WAS INVENTED</i>   
<i> BY THE BRITISH FOR THEIR NAVY.</i> 

276
00:11:57,884 --> 00:11:59,951
             THEIR CARRONADE WAS
             ACTUALLY ATTACHED  

277
00:12:00,019 --> 00:12:01,652
                    TO THE DECK 
                    OF THE SHIP.

278
00:12:01,721 --> 00:12:03,688
       AND IT WOULD ACTUALLY BE 
       PINNED AT THE FRONT OF IT

279
00:12:03,756 --> 00:12:05,389
                 AND THEN SWIVEL
                 ON THAT PIN    

280
00:12:05,458 --> 00:12:07,625
       TO PREVENT IT FROM MOVING
       AROUND ON THE SHIP.      

281
00:12:07,694 --> 00:12:09,460
      IT WAS THE OLD EXPRESSION,
      "LOOSE CANNONS,"          

282
00:12:09,529 --> 00:12:10,995
        AND THAT WAS EXACTLY IT,

283
00:12:11,064 --> 00:12:12,697
         THAT WAS THE LAST THING
         YOU WANTED ON A SHIP   

284
00:12:12,765 --> 00:12:14,598
   HEAVING IN THE WAVES         
   WAS A CANNON BOUNCING AROUND.

285
00:12:14,667 --> 00:12:16,367
             SO THE NAVY TOOK   
             THE ADDITIONAL STEP

286
00:12:16,436 --> 00:12:18,436
     AND WOULD ACTUALLY PIN THEM
     TO THE DECK.               

287
00:12:18,504 --> 00:12:20,972
        <i> DAVE EXPLAINS</i>          
       <i> HOW THIS WORKED.</i>        

288
00:12:21,040 --> 00:12:23,441
  <i> A THREADED PIN AT THE BACK</i>   
        <i> OF THE BARREL</i>          

289
00:12:23,509 --> 00:12:25,276
      <i> ADJUSTED THE TILT.</i>       

290
00:12:25,345 --> 00:12:29,447
  <i> THE BARREL WAS MOUNTED ON</i>    
   <i> A SMALL BASE, OR SLIDER,</i>    

291
00:12:29,515 --> 00:12:32,216
   <i> WHICH FIT ONTO A LONGER</i>     
        <i> SLOTTED BOARD.</i>         

292
00:12:32,285 --> 00:12:34,518
  <i> THIS BOARD SAT ON ROLLERS</i>    
         <i> AT THE BACK</i>           

293
00:12:34,587 --> 00:12:36,487
         <i> AND PIVOTED</i>           
        <i> AT THE FRONT.</i>          

294
00:12:36,556 --> 00:12:38,789
     <i> ANOTHER PIN BENEATH</i>       
        <i> THE CARRONADE</i>          

295
00:12:38,858 --> 00:12:41,058
     <i> WENT FROM THE SLIDER</i>      
        <i> INTO THE SLOT.</i>         

296
00:12:41,127 --> 00:12:43,995
  <i> WHEN THE CARRONADE FIRED,</i>    
 <i> THIS CONTROLLED THE RECOIL.</i>   

297
00:12:44,063 --> 00:12:48,165
<i> DAVE SAYS THE RECENT FINDS SHOW</i>
 <i> SIMILARITIES TO THIS DESIGN.</i>  

298
00:12:48,234 --> 00:12:50,534
     THEY STILL HAVE THAT SLIDER
     ATTACHED TO IT,            

299
00:12:50,603 --> 00:12:52,536
            OR AT LEAST EVIDENCE
            OF THAT.            

300
00:12:52,605 --> 00:12:55,740
  THAT BRINGS THE PROBABILITY   
  OF THIS BEING A U.S. NAVY SHIP

301
00:12:55,808 --> 00:12:58,576
               MUCH, MUCH HIGHER
               IN OUR EYES.     

302
00:12:58,644 --> 00:13:01,712
 <i> BUT WITH ALL THE CONCRETION</i>   
<i> SURROUNDING MIRANDA'S OBJECT,</i>  

303
00:13:01,781 --> 00:13:04,915
   <i> IT'S IMPOSSIBLE TO MAKE</i>     
   <i> A DEFINITIVE CONNECTION.</i>    

304
00:13:04,984 --> 00:13:09,253
       <i> MY INVESTIGATION</i>        
     <i> MIGHT BE AT AN END.</i>       

305
00:13:09,322 --> 00:13:12,790
     <i> BUT BECAUSE INTEREST</i>      
  <i> IN MIRANDA'S FIND IS HIGH,</i>   

306
00:13:12,859 --> 00:13:16,861
<i> I'VE BEEN ABLE TO SCHEDULE AN</i>  
<i> X-RAY SESSION FOR THE CANNONS.</i> 

307
00:13:16,929 --> 00:13:20,030
 <i> I'M RETURNING TO NEHALEM BAY</i>  
   <i> TO MEET ROBERT NEYLAND,</i>     

308
00:13:20,099 --> 00:13:22,666
    <i> HEAD OF THE UNDERWATER</i>     
      <i> ARCHEOLOGY BRANCH</i>        

309
00:13:22,735 --> 00:13:24,468
         <i> OF THE NAVAL</i>          
      <i> HISTORICAL CENTER,</i>       

310
00:13:24,537 --> 00:13:26,303
       <i> WHO WILL EXAMINE</i>        
         <i> THE X-RAYS.</i>           

311
00:13:26,372 --> 00:13:29,039
THIS IS JUST                    
A GENERIC CARRONADE.            

312
00:13:29,108 --> 00:13:31,108
         <i> BOB TELLS ME</i>          
      <i> THESE WERE COMMON</i>        

313
00:13:31,177 --> 00:13:33,210
      <i> ON MANY NAVY SHIPS</i>       
        <i> LIKE THE</i> SHARK         

314
00:13:33,279 --> 00:13:35,446
      <i> IN THE FIRST HALF</i>        
     <i> OF THE 19th CENTURY.</i>      

315
00:13:35,515 --> 00:13:37,748
IN A CLOSE-IN FIGHT,            
THEY WOULD DO MORE DAMAGE       

316
00:13:37,817 --> 00:13:39,750
TO THE OPPOSING                 
OR THE ENEMY SHIP               

317
00:13:39,819 --> 00:13:41,719
AND DO MORE DAMAGE              
TO THE CREWS, TOO.              

318
00:13:41,788 --> 00:13:44,255
IT WOULD SMASH UP THE WOOD      
OR THE SHIP A LOT MORE.         

319
00:13:44,323 --> 00:13:47,124
  <i> BECAUSE THIS SMALL CANNON</i>    
    <i> WAS A POPULAR WEAPON,</i>      

320
00:13:47,193 --> 00:13:50,094
     <i> BOB SAYS MATCHING IT</i>      
 <i> TO THE</i> SHARK<i> WILL BE TOUGH.</i>   

321
00:13:50,163 --> 00:13:52,329
     <i> BUT ONCE THE X-RAYS</i>       
       <i> HAVE PENETRATED</i>         

322
00:13:52,398 --> 00:13:54,832
     <i> MORE THAN 150 YEARS</i>       
         <i> OF DEPOSITS,</i>          

323
00:13:54,901 --> 00:13:57,268
       <i> THEY MAY REVEAL</i>         
      <i> SOMETHING TELLING.</i>       

324
00:13:57,336 --> 00:14:00,104
YOU COULD GET LUCKY AND ACTUALLY
SEE A DATE MARKED ON THE GUNS   

325
00:14:00,173 --> 00:14:01,639
AS WELL AS FOUNDRY MARKS.       

326
00:14:01,707 --> 00:14:03,107
YOU COULD GET LUCKY             
AND SEE THAT.                   

327
00:14:03,176 --> 00:14:05,075
           THAT'D BE VERY LUCKY.
YEAH, IT WOULD BE.              

328
00:14:05,144 --> 00:14:07,945
YOU KNOW, OR SAY "U.S. NAVY"    
AS WELL, TOO.                   

329
00:14:08,014 --> 00:14:11,015
 <i> TO CAPTURE A GLIMPSE OF THE</i>   
<i> OBJECT BENEATH THIS THICK MASS</i> 

330
00:14:11,083 --> 00:14:13,884
    <i> REQUIRES AN EXTREMELY</i>      
     <i> HIGH-POWERED SYSTEM.</i>      

331
00:14:13,953 --> 00:14:16,787
    <i> A TEAM OF SPECIALISTS</i>      
      <i> IN NUCLEAR IMAGING</i>       

332
00:14:16,856 --> 00:14:20,291
      <i> FROM FUJIFILM NDT</i>        
     <i> AND PSI INCORPORATED</i>      

333
00:14:20,359 --> 00:14:25,029
       <i> ARE VOLUNTEERING</i>        
   <i> THEIR EXPERTISE TO HELP.</i>    

334
00:14:25,097 --> 00:14:28,232
<i> BOB EXAMINES MIRANDA'S CANNON</i>  
     <i> TO PLAN THE X-RAYS.</i>       

335
00:14:28,301 --> 00:14:30,467
HERE YOU'VE GOT YOUR PIN        
FOR THE CARRIAGE.               

336
00:14:30,536 --> 00:14:32,770
THIS APPEARS TO BE WHAT'S LEFT  
OF YOUR BREACH RING,            

337
00:14:32,838 --> 00:14:34,605
BUT IT LOOKS LIKE               
A PIECE OF IT'S BROKEN OFF      

338
00:14:34,674 --> 00:14:36,340
IF I'M CORRECT IN THAT.         

339
00:14:36,409 --> 00:14:38,209
THE SCREW,                      
THE ELEVATING SCREW,            

340
00:14:38,277 --> 00:14:41,178
SHOULD BE RIGHT IN HERE         
SOMEWHERE AS WELL, TOO.         

341
00:14:45,918 --> 00:14:47,751
      YOU GUYS ARE GOING        
      TO HAVE TO BACK OFF.      

342
00:14:47,820 --> 00:14:50,087
      IT'S GOING TO GET         
      REAL HOT RIGHT HERE.      

343
00:14:50,156 --> 00:14:52,756
 <i> THE FILM NEEDS TO BE EXPOSED</i>  
    <i> FOR NEARLY 90 MINUTES</i>      

344
00:14:52,825 --> 00:14:54,925
  <i> TO CAPTURE ENOUGH DETAIL.</i>    

345
00:14:54,994 --> 00:14:57,261
  <i> WHEN ALL OF THE EXPOSURES</i>    
    <i> ARE FINALLY COMPLETE,</i>      

346
00:14:57,330 --> 00:15:00,831
   <i> WE TAKE THE X-RAY PLATES</i>    
 <i> INSIDE TO SEE WHAT WE HAVE.</i>   

347
00:15:00,900 --> 00:15:02,299
STILL NOT GETTING               
ANYTHING, HUH?                  

348
00:15:02,368 --> 00:15:03,601
   I CAN SEE A LITTLE MORE.     

349
00:15:03,669 --> 00:15:05,269
       <i> THE FIRST IMAGE</i>         
       <i> REVEALS LITTLE.</i>         

350
00:15:05,338 --> 00:15:07,805
     <i> THE SECOND PLATE IS</i>       
    <i> ONLY SLIGHTLY BETTER,</i>      

351
00:15:07,873 --> 00:15:10,574
     <i> BUT IT DOES OUTLINE</i>       
<i> THE SHAPE OF A CANNON BARREL.</i>  

352
00:15:10,643 --> 00:15:13,611
         IN THIS SHOT, WE'VE GOT
         SOME OF THE BORE,      

353
00:15:13,679 --> 00:15:15,913
   WE'RE DEFINITELY LOOKING AT  
   THE BANDING AROUND THE GUN...

354
00:15:15,982 --> 00:15:21,385
 <i> THE BANDING KEPT THE BARREL</i>   
  <i> FROM RUPTURING WHEN FIRED.</i>   

355
00:15:21,454 --> 00:15:26,457
          <i> WE'RE DOWN</i>           
      <i> TO THE LAST PLATE.</i>       

356
00:15:26,525 --> 00:15:28,659
     THAT IS A GREAT SHOT.      

357
00:15:28,728 --> 00:15:30,294
              NOW WE'RE TALKING.

358
00:15:30,363 --> 00:15:33,030
      <i> IT'S TIME TO GIVE</i>        
     <i> MIRANDA HER ANSWER.</i>       

359
00:15:33,099 --> 00:15:36,233
I HAVE DONE ALL THE RESEARCH    
THAT WAS POSSIBLE               

360
00:15:36,302 --> 00:15:37,935
ON THE CANNON                   
THAT YOU FOUND.                 

361
00:15:38,004 --> 00:15:39,536
BUT THIS IS NOT                 
JUST A CANNON,                  

362
00:15:39,605 --> 00:15:42,640
IT'S A CERTAIN KIND OF CANNON   
CALLED A CARRONADE              

363
00:15:42,708 --> 00:15:45,309
THAT WAS ON U.S. NAVY SHIPS     

364
00:15:45,378 --> 00:15:48,445
IN THE EARLY HALF               
OF THE 19th CENTURY.            

365
00:15:48,514 --> 00:15:51,315
     <i> I TELL MIRANDA ABOUT</i>      
     <i> THE</i> USS SHARK'S<i> ROLE</i>      

366
00:15:51,384 --> 00:15:53,183
        <i> IN THE SHAPING</i>         
     <i> OF AMERICA'S BORDERS</i>      

367
00:15:53,252 --> 00:15:55,019
  <i> AND ITS FOREIGN RELATIONS.</i>   

368
00:15:55,087 --> 00:15:57,755
  <i> ONLY VERY POWERFUL X-RAYS</i>    
       <i> COULD PEER DEEP</i>         

369
00:15:57,823 --> 00:16:00,157
  <i> INTO THE MASS OF SEDIMENT</i>    
       <i> AND RUSTED METAL</i>        

370
00:16:00,226 --> 00:16:02,760
     <i> TO REVEAL WHAT LIES</i>       
         <i> UNDERNEATH.</i>           

371
00:16:02,828 --> 00:16:04,261
        SO WHAT ARE WE          
        LOOKING AT HERE?        

372
00:16:04,330 --> 00:16:05,462
             THERE'S YOUR SCREW.

373
00:16:05,531 --> 00:16:06,730
          EXCELLENT.            

374
00:16:06,799 --> 00:16:08,499
I GUESS THIS IS THE THREADING   
ON IT, RIGHT?                   

375
00:16:08,567 --> 00:16:10,601
  YOU CAN CLEARLY SEE           
  YOU'VE STILL GOT THE THREADS  

376
00:16:10,669 --> 00:16:12,102
     VERY VISIBLE IN HERE.      

377
00:16:12,171 --> 00:16:13,771
           OH, THAT'S WHERE     
           YOU'D CRANK IT, OKAY.

378
00:16:13,839 --> 00:16:15,506
      THE LOOP HERE             
      FOR THE BREACH ROPE,      

379
00:16:15,574 --> 00:16:16,940
      A LONG GUN WOULDN'T       
      HAVE THAT.                

380
00:16:17,009 --> 00:16:18,242
     THE ELEVATING SCREW,       

381
00:16:18,310 --> 00:16:20,010
   A LONG GUN WOULD NOT HAVE    
   AN ELEVATING SCREW.          

382
00:16:20,079 --> 00:16:21,478
        IT'S DEFINITELY         
        A CARRONADE.            

383
00:16:21,547 --> 00:16:23,047
      BUT IT ALSO COMPARES      
      VERY FAVORABLY            

384
00:16:23,115 --> 00:16:25,749
   TO THE CANNON THAT           
   WAS RECOVERED IN THE 1890s   

385
00:16:25,818 --> 00:16:28,652
     AND IS NOW AN EXHIBIT,     
     SO SUGGESTING IT IS        

386
00:16:28,721 --> 00:16:32,122
  THE SAME TIME OF CANNON,      
  PERHAPS FROM THE SAME SHIP.   

387
00:16:32,191 --> 00:16:34,091
   I DON'T SEE ANYWHERE         
   WHERE IT SAYS<i> "USS SHARK"</i>    

388
00:16:34,160 --> 00:16:36,427
   OR "U.S. NAVY,"              
   BUT THIS IS ALL CONSISTENT   

389
00:16:36,495 --> 00:16:38,362
      WITH THE CARRONADE.       

390
00:16:38,431 --> 00:16:40,964
   SO FAR, CIRCUMSTANTIAL       
   EVIDENCE, IT IS CONSISTENT   

391
00:16:41,033 --> 00:16:43,967
WITH WHAT WE'D EXPECT TO SEE    
FOR A CARRONADE FROM THE<i> SHARK.</i> 

392
00:16:44,036 --> 00:16:47,738
AND HERE IS AN X-RAY            
OF THE PART OF THE CANNON       

393
00:16:47,807 --> 00:16:49,873
THAT WOULD GO INTO              
THE DECK THERE.                 

394
00:16:49,942 --> 00:16:52,109
YOU WOULD SCREW IT              
TO LIFT IT UP.                  

395
00:16:52,178 --> 00:16:53,744
              THAT'S AWESOME.   

396
00:16:53,813 --> 00:16:55,212
               THANK YOU.       

397
00:16:55,281 --> 00:16:58,949
ALL THE PEOPLE AGREE THAT       
WHILE WE'LL NEVER KNOW FOR SURE,

398
00:16:59,018 --> 00:17:02,586
YOU PROBABLY FOUND THE CANNON   
THAT WAS ON THE<i> USS SHARK.</i>      

399
00:17:02,655 --> 00:17:04,221
       NICE, THAT'S PRETTY COOL.

400
00:17:04,290 --> 00:17:06,190
DON'T YOU FEEL PROUD ABOUT THAT?
              YEAH, THAT'S COOL.

401
00:17:06,258 --> 00:17:08,659
YOU FOUND SOMETHING             
THAT DOESN'T JUST GIVE US       

402
00:17:08,727 --> 00:17:11,662
A CRITICAL PART OF              
THE EARLY HISTORY OF OREGON     

403
00:17:11,730 --> 00:17:15,232
BUT TELLS US ABOUT              
A VERY IMPORTANT PART           

404
00:17:15,301 --> 00:17:17,401
OF AMERICAN HISTORY.            

405
00:17:17,470 --> 00:17:19,036
              WOW, ONE CANNON.  

406
00:17:19,104 --> 00:17:21,839
YEAH.                           

407
00:17:21,907 --> 00:17:24,241
       <i> THE GREAT IRONY</i>         
     <i> OF THE</i> SHARK'S<i> STORY</i>      

408
00:17:24,310 --> 00:17:26,577
      <i> WAS THAT A TREATY</i>        
      <i> ENDING THE DISPUTE</i>       

409
00:17:26,645 --> 00:17:30,714
   <i> OVER THE CANADIAN BORDER</i>    
 <i> WAS SIGNED IN JUNE OF 1846,</i>   

410
00:17:30,783 --> 00:17:34,751
  <i> ONE MONTH BEFORE THE</i> SHARK   
<i> ARRIVED AT THE COLUMBIA RIVER.</i> 

411
00:17:34,820 --> 00:17:37,421
      <i> NEWS DIDN'T REACH</i>        
      <i> LIEUTENANT HOWISON</i>       

412
00:17:37,489 --> 00:17:40,424
        <i> UNTIL A MONTH</i>          
    <i> AFTER THE</i> SHARK<i> SANK.</i>      

413
00:17:40,492 --> 00:17:43,660
    <i> THE OREGON TREATY SET</i>      
   <i> THE U.S./CANADIAN BORDER</i>    

414
00:17:43,729 --> 00:17:47,731
    <i> AT THE 49th PARALLEL,</i>      
   <i> WHERE IT REMAINS TODAY.</i>     

415
00:17:50,069 --> 00:17:53,370
   SOME OF THE WORLD'S MOST     
FASCINATING HISTORICAL OBJECTS  

416
00:17:53,439 --> 00:17:55,706
         HAVE EMERGED           
        FROM THE DEEP.          

417
00:17:55,774 --> 00:17:58,242
   OCEANS, RIVERS, AND LAKES    
           ARE TOMBS            

418
00:17:58,310 --> 00:18:01,211
  FOR AN INCALCULABLE WEALTH    
          OF OBJECTS.           

419
00:18:01,280 --> 00:18:04,781
 ALTHOUGH UNDERWATER RECOVERY   
      IS NOT ALWAYS EASY,       

420
00:18:04,850 --> 00:18:08,619
    ADVANCES IN TECHNOLOGY      
 HAVE MADE MARITIME ARCHEOLOGY  

421
00:18:08,687 --> 00:18:12,522
   AN EXCITING NEW FRONTIER     
        FOR HISTORIANS.         

422
00:18:12,591 --> 00:18:16,293
   IN 1943, JACQUES COUSTEAU    
       AND EMILE GAGNON         

423
00:18:16,362 --> 00:18:18,862
        REVOLUTIONIZED          
    UNDERWATER EXPLORATION      

424
00:18:18,931 --> 00:18:20,998
     WITH THEIR AQUA-LUNG,      

425
00:18:21,066 --> 00:18:24,201
  A SELF-CONTAINED UNDERWATER   
     BREATHING APPARATUS.       

426
00:18:24,270 --> 00:18:27,004
       THIS SCUBA DEVICE        
 ALLOWED HUMANS TO FREELY DIVE  

427
00:18:27,072 --> 00:18:29,740
    TO DEPTHS OF 180 FEET.      

428
00:18:29,808 --> 00:18:31,541
    THE NEXT GREAT ADVANCE      

429
00:18:31,610 --> 00:18:34,044
    WAS TITANIUM-REINFORCED     
         SUBMERSIBLES,          

430
00:18:34,113 --> 00:18:37,180
   WHICH COULD PROBE TWO AND    
 A HALF MILES BELOW SEA LEVEL.  

431
00:18:37,249 --> 00:18:40,884
           IN 1985,             
    AN UNMANNED SUBMERSIBLE     

432
00:18:40,953 --> 00:18:43,954
     FINALLY MADE CONTACT       
       WITH THE<i> TITANIC.</i>        

433
00:18:44,023 --> 00:18:47,024
 THE NOTION THAT A GREAT GASH   
  HAD RIPPED THE SHIP IN TWO    

434
00:18:47,092 --> 00:18:48,859
       WAS NOW DEBUNKED.        

435
00:18:48,927 --> 00:18:53,063
   IN 2002, ONE OF HISTORY'S    
 MOST SIGNIFICANT DISCOVERIES   

436
00:18:53,132 --> 00:18:55,832
           WAS MADE             
      BY SHEER ACCIDENT.        

437
00:18:55,901 --> 00:18:59,803
      OFF INDIA'S COAST,        
   OCEANOGRAPHERS UNEARTHED     

438
00:18:59,872 --> 00:19:04,074
   WHAT COULD BE ONE OF THE     
 WORLD'S OLDEST CIVILIZATIONS.  

439
00:19:04,143 --> 00:19:06,677
     SCIENTISTS USED SONAR      
          TO IDENTIFY           

440
00:19:06,745 --> 00:19:12,616
   HUGE GEOMETRIC STRUCTURES    
   DATING BACK 10,000 YEARS.    

441
00:19:16,455 --> 00:19:19,156
            Elyse:              
        <i> OUR NEXT STORY</i>         
         <i> INVESTIGATES</i>          

442
00:19:19,224 --> 00:19:23,160
   <i> A CONNECTICUT FARMHOUSE</i>     
   <i> WITH AN UNSETTLED PAST.</i>     

443
00:19:26,465 --> 00:19:28,198
  <i> AS THE 20th CENTURY DAWNS,</i>   

444
00:19:28,267 --> 00:19:30,233
       <i> AMERICA'S CITIES</i>        
     <i> ARE INDUSTRIALIZING</i>       

445
00:19:30,302 --> 00:19:32,703
        <i> AND GROWING AT</i>         
      <i> AN EXPLOSIVE RATE.</i>       

446
00:19:32,771 --> 00:19:34,971
     <i> THEY'RE BEING FILLED</i>      
       <i> BY A TIDAL WAVE</i>         

447
00:19:35,040 --> 00:19:38,041
  <i> OF IMMIGRANTS FROM EUROPE</i>    
  <i> AND NATIVE-BORN AMERICANS</i>    

448
00:19:38,110 --> 00:19:40,143
      <i> WHO ARE ABANDONING</i>       
      <i> THEIR FAMILY FARMS</i>       

449
00:19:40,212 --> 00:19:42,245
     <i> FOR THE OPPORTUNITY</i>       
       <i> AND BETTER WAGES</i>        

450
00:19:42,314 --> 00:19:46,550
<i> OF THE INDUSTRIAL REVOLUTION.</i>  

451
00:19:46,618 --> 00:19:48,919
  <i> MORE THAN 100 YEARS LATER,</i>   

452
00:19:48,987 --> 00:19:51,288
  <i> CHRIS REMY OF EAST HADDAM,</i>   
         <i> CONNECTICUT,</i>          

453
00:19:51,356 --> 00:19:53,957
      <i> BELIEVES HIS HOME</i>        
   <i> MAY SOMEHOW BE CONNECTED</i>    

454
00:19:54,026 --> 00:19:56,760
   <i> TO THIS DRAMATIC PERIOD</i>     
      <i> IN AMERICA'S PAST.</i>       

455
00:19:56,829 --> 00:19:58,495
               I'D LIKE TO KNOW 
               A LITTLE BIT MORE

456
00:19:58,564 --> 00:19:59,830
               ABOUT THE HISTORY
               OF MY HOUSE,     

457
00:19:59,898 --> 00:20:02,499
             WHO WERE THE PEOPLE
             THAT LIVED HERE.   

458
00:20:03,769 --> 00:20:05,035
                  HI.           
I'M ELYSE.                      

459
00:20:05,104 --> 00:20:06,403
              CHRIS, COME ON IN.

460
00:20:06,472 --> 00:20:08,405
WHAT A GREAT HOUSE.             
                      THANK YOU.

461
00:20:08,474 --> 00:20:10,040
SO HOW LONG HAVE YOU            
OWNED IT?                       

462
00:20:10,109 --> 00:20:11,641
             WE BOUGHT THE HOUSE
             SIX YEARS AGO.     

463
00:20:11,710 --> 00:20:15,812
  IT'S FIVE ACRES, PART OF WHAT 
  WAS ORIGINALLY A 60-ACRE FARM.

464
00:20:15,881 --> 00:20:17,848
THIS IS THE MAP FROM            
WHEN THEY SUBDIVIDED IT         

465
00:20:17,916 --> 00:20:19,382
BACK IN THE '70s,               

466
00:20:19,451 --> 00:20:21,818
AND HERE'S OUR FIVE-ACRE PLOT   
RIGHT HERE.                     

467
00:20:21,887 --> 00:20:23,753
      WHAT SPARKED YOUR INTEREST
      IN DOING RESEARCH?        

468
00:20:23,822 --> 00:20:25,956
WELL, I KNEW THE HOUSE          
WAS BUILT IN 1804, OBVIOUSLY,   

469
00:20:26,024 --> 00:20:28,024
WHEN I BOUGHT IT,               
SO I WANTED TO RESEARCH         

470
00:20:28,093 --> 00:20:30,327
WHAT I COULD FIND OUT,          
WHO BUILT IT AND WHEN,          

471
00:20:30,395 --> 00:20:31,661
AND WHO'S LIVED HERE.           

472
00:20:31,730 --> 00:20:32,996
            WHAT'D YOU FIND OUT?

473
00:20:33,065 --> 00:20:34,831
WELL, I FOUND OUT THAT AROUND   
THE TURN OF THE LAST CENTURY,   

474
00:20:34,900 --> 00:20:37,200
THE PROPERTY SEEMED TO          
CHANGE HANDS A LOT OF TIMES --  

475
00:20:37,269 --> 00:20:38,702
EVERY YEAR,                     
EVERY TWO YEARS --              

476
00:20:38,770 --> 00:20:40,303
FOR A GOOD 15, 20 YEARS,        

477
00:20:40,372 --> 00:20:43,073
AND THEY SEEMED TO HAVE RUSSIAN 
AND EASTERN-EUROPEAN NAMES.     

478
00:20:43,141 --> 00:20:44,941
     WHAT SPECIFICALLY          
     DO YOU WANT ME TO FIND OUT?

479
00:20:45,010 --> 00:20:46,443
I'D LIKE TO KNOW                
WHO THESE PEOPLE WERE,          

480
00:20:46,512 --> 00:20:47,944
WHAT WERE THEY                  
DOING HERE...                   

481
00:20:48,013 --> 00:20:49,112
                    MM-HMM.     

482
00:20:49,181 --> 00:20:51,248
AND WHY DID THE PROPERTY        
CHANGE HANDS SO MANY TIMES      

483
00:20:51,316 --> 00:20:53,016
IN SUCH A SHORT                 
TIME FRAME?                     

484
00:20:53,085 --> 00:20:54,751
       DO YOU HAVE ANYTHING ELSE
       FOR ME TO GO ON?         

485
00:20:54,820 --> 00:20:57,087
WELL, WHEN I WAS DOING          
SOME REMODELING ON THE HOUSE,   

486
00:20:57,155 --> 00:21:00,323
INSIDE THE WALLS, I FOUND       
THIS OLD WALLPAPER.             

487
00:21:00,392 --> 00:21:03,994
ON THE OTHER SIDE IS NEWSPAPER  
WITH HEBREW CHARACTERS.         

488
00:21:04,062 --> 00:21:05,962
AND AT THE TOP OF THIS PAGE     
YOU CAN SEE                     

489
00:21:06,031 --> 00:21:07,731
IT'S<i> THE JEWISH</i>                 
<i> MORNING JOURNAL.</i>               

490
00:21:07,799 --> 00:21:10,000
 WELL, I'M GOING TO GO WALK     
 OUTSIDE AND TAKE A LOOK AROUND,

491
00:21:10,068 --> 00:21:12,002
        AND THEN I GUESS I'M OFF
        TO THE TOWN HALL.       

492
00:21:12,070 --> 00:21:14,671
OKAY.                           

493
00:21:14,740 --> 00:21:17,407
  <i> I'M ESPECIALLY INTERESTED</i>    
        <i> IN THIS STORY.</i>         

494
00:21:17,476 --> 00:21:19,576
    <i> MY OWN FAMILY ARRIVED</i>      
     <i> FROM EASTERN EUROPE</i>       

495
00:21:19,645 --> 00:21:22,012
 <i> AND SETTLED IN NEW YORK CITY</i>  
   <i> AND BALTIMORE, MARYLAND,</i>    

496
00:21:22,080 --> 00:21:24,114
    <i> THREE GENERATIONS AGO.</i>     

497
00:21:24,182 --> 00:21:26,750
<i> BUT IT'S NOT CLEAR WHY SO MANY</i> 
<i> EASTERN-EUROPEAN IMMIGRANTS --</i> 

498
00:21:26,818 --> 00:21:28,418
        <i> IF THAT'S WHAT</i>         
         <i> THEY WERE --</i>          

499
00:21:28,487 --> 00:21:31,621
<i> ROTATED THROUGH THIS FARMHOUSE</i> 
 <i> AT THE TURN OF THE CENTURY.</i>   

500
00:21:33,825 --> 00:21:37,127
        <i> MY FIRST STOP</i>          
        <i> IS TOWN HALL.</i>          

501
00:21:37,195 --> 00:21:42,432
  <i> THERE ARE LAND DEEDS HERE</i>    
  <i> GOING BACK TWO CENTURIES.</i>    

502
00:21:42,501 --> 00:21:45,201
        <i> BEFORE I SCOUR</i>         
     <i> THESE BOUND RECORDS,</i>      

503
00:21:45,270 --> 00:21:47,671
     <i> I WANT TO LEARN MORE</i>      
   <i> ABOUT THE OLD NEWSPAPERS</i>    

504
00:21:47,739 --> 00:21:50,206
    <i> FROM INSIDE THE WALLS</i>      
        <i> OF THE HOUSE.</i>          

505
00:21:50,275 --> 00:21:51,941
  <i> THE JEWISH MORNING JOURNAL</i>   

506
00:21:52,010 --> 00:21:54,177
        WAS APPARENTLY          
  AN ULTRA-ORTHODOX NEWSPAPER   

507
00:21:54,246 --> 00:21:56,246
     THAT STARTED PRINTING      
     IN THE UNITED STATES       

508
00:21:56,315 --> 00:21:58,181
       IN NEW YORK CITY         
           IN 1902.             

509
00:21:58,250 --> 00:21:59,783
        LISTEN TO THIS:         

510
00:21:59,851 --> 00:22:01,785
   THE PAPER WASN'T WRITTEN     
          IN HEBREW,            

511
00:22:01,853 --> 00:22:03,653
    IT WAS ACTUALLY WRITTEN     
          IN YIDDISH.           

512
00:22:03,722 --> 00:22:05,955
      YIDDISH IS WRITTEN        
    WITH HEBREW CHARACTERS,     

513
00:22:06,024 --> 00:22:07,691
     BUT IT IS DIFFERENT.       

514
00:22:07,759 --> 00:22:10,026
       IT'S DERIVED FROM        
     THE GERMAN LANGUAGE.       

515
00:22:10,095 --> 00:22:12,295
     THERE'S PROBABLY ONLY      
   A QUARTER-MILLION PEOPLE     

516
00:22:12,364 --> 00:22:14,864
     IN THE UNITED STATES       
   TODAY THAT SPEAK YIDDISH,    

517
00:22:14,933 --> 00:22:16,933
   INCLUDING MY GRANDMOTHER.    

518
00:22:17,002 --> 00:22:18,535
       <i> I KNOW FROM HER</i>         
       <i> THAT BACK THEN,</i>         

519
00:22:18,603 --> 00:22:20,203
         <i> THE LANGUAGE</i>          
      <i> WAS SPOKEN WIDELY</i>        

520
00:22:20,272 --> 00:22:22,906
   <i> AMONG JEWISH IMMIGRANTS</i>     
     <i> FROM EASTERN EUROPE.</i>      

521
00:22:22,974 --> 00:22:26,176
     ALL RIGHT, LET'S SEE       
WHAT THE LAND DEEDS CAN TELL US.

522
00:22:26,244 --> 00:22:29,379
   <i> HERE'S THE FIRST RECORD</i>     
   <i> OF THE SALE OF THE LAND.</i>    

523
00:22:29,448 --> 00:22:32,048
       ON JULY 17, 1798,        

524
00:22:32,117 --> 00:22:34,984
JUSTIN WORTHINGTON SOLD THE LAND
       TO CIRUS WILLEY.         

525
00:22:35,053 --> 00:22:36,820
      <i> THE FARM STAYED IN</i>       
        <i> THE SAME HANDS</i>         

526
00:22:36,888 --> 00:22:38,822
 <i> FOR MORE THAN THREE-QUARTERS</i>  
        <i> OF A CENTURY.</i>          

527
00:22:38,890 --> 00:22:42,492
      <i> THE WILLEY FAMILY</i>        
    <i> SOLD THE FARM IN 1878,</i>     

528
00:22:42,561 --> 00:22:45,462
     <i> AND THE REAL ESTATE</i>       
<i> TRANSACTIONS LOOK PRETTY NORMAL</i>

529
00:22:45,530 --> 00:22:47,931
         <i> UNTIL 1891.</i>           

530
00:22:47,999 --> 00:22:50,734
       ON JUNE 15, 1891,        

531
00:22:50,802 --> 00:22:55,972
    IT LOOKS LIKE THE LAND      
   WAS SOLD TO DAVID DINSON.    

532
00:22:56,041 --> 00:22:58,742
   <i> ONLY FOUR MONTHS LATER,</i>     
    <i> DINSON SELLS THE FARM</i>      

533
