711
00:30:40,638 --> 00:30:42,504
          IN A VERY JEWISH AREA,

712
00:30:42,573 --> 00:30:44,073
                BUT THEN TO MOVE
                TO THE COUNTRY  

713
00:30:44,141 --> 00:30:45,674
           WAS A VERY HARD MOVE.

714
00:30:45,743 --> 00:30:47,543
    SUDDENLY, THEY'RE IN        
    THE CONNECTICUT COUNTRYSIDE,

715
00:30:47,612 --> 00:30:49,979
    WHERE THERE'S NOT A         
    READY-MADE JEWISH COMMUNITY,

716
00:30:50,047 --> 00:30:52,047
                THEY DIDN'T     
                SPEAK ENGLISH --

717
00:30:52,116 --> 00:30:53,582
            THAT MADE IT HARDER.

718
00:30:53,651 --> 00:30:55,651
       <i> BUT MARY DOUBTS</i>         
 <i> RESENTMENT OF THE NEWCOMERS</i>   

719
00:30:55,720 --> 00:30:57,586
        <i> WAS THE REASON</i>         
    <i> FOR THE HIGH TURNOVER.</i>     

720
00:30:57,655 --> 00:30:59,488
              I THINK IF        
              THE JEWISH FARMERS

721
00:30:59,557 --> 00:31:01,323
              WORKED HARD AND   
              BECAME SUCCESSFUL,

722
00:31:01,392 --> 00:31:03,692
    THEY REALLY HAD             
    THE YANKEE FARMERS' RESPECT.

723
00:31:03,761 --> 00:31:05,527
       <i> BUT IF IT WASN'T</i>        
         <i> XENOPHOBIA,</i>           

724
00:31:05,596 --> 00:31:08,097
   <i> WHY WEREN'T THE FAMILIES</i>    
<i> WHO LIVED IN CHRIS'S FARMHOUSE</i> 

725
00:31:08,165 --> 00:31:10,165
      <i> ABLE TO MAKE A GO</i>        
            <i> OF IT?</i>             

726
00:31:10,234 --> 00:31:12,601
           THE REAL BREAKTHROUGH
           CAME THROUGH IN 1908.

727
00:31:12,670 --> 00:31:14,203
   <i> WHAT MARY TELLS ME NEXT</i>     

728
00:31:14,272 --> 00:31:16,805
     <i> PUTS ALL THE PIECES</i>       
   <i> OF THE PUZZLE IN PLACE.</i>     

729
00:31:16,874 --> 00:31:19,775
    <i> IT'S TIME TO HEAD BACK</i>     
          <i> TO CHRIS.</i>            

730
00:31:19,844 --> 00:31:21,844
CHRIS, I WASN'T ABLE TO FIND OUT
A LOT OF INFORMATION            

731
00:31:21,912 --> 00:31:23,579
           ABOUT THE PEOPLE THAT
           LIVED HERE,          

732
00:31:23,648 --> 00:31:25,781
         BUT YOU WERE RIGHT,    
         THEY WERE RUSSIAN JEWS.

733
00:31:25,850 --> 00:31:26,982
THAT'S GREAT.                   

734
00:31:27,051 --> 00:31:28,484
             PRETTY COOL, RIGHT?
PRETTY COOL.                    

735
00:31:28,552 --> 00:31:30,986
      <i> I TELL CHRIS HOW,</i>        
<i> WITH THE HELP OF ORGANIZATIONS</i> 

736
00:31:31,055 --> 00:31:33,122
       <i> LIKE THE JEWISH</i>         
    <i> AGRICULTURAL SOCIETY,</i>      

737
00:31:33,190 --> 00:31:35,724
   <i> IMMIGRANTS ESCAPED FROM</i>     
  <i> THE SLUMS OF NEW YORK CITY</i>   

738
00:31:35,793 --> 00:31:37,626
    <i> TO FARMS SUCH AS HIS.</i>      

739
00:31:37,695 --> 00:31:40,062
       BUT WHEN THEY GOT HERE,  
       IT WAS A DIFFERENT STORY.

740
00:31:40,131 --> 00:31:42,631
         THEY REALLY DIDN'T HAVE
         TRAINING AS FARMERS,   

741
00:31:42,700 --> 00:31:44,800
            AND THESE ARE PEOPLE
            THAT WERE REFUGEES. 

742
00:31:44,869 --> 00:31:47,202
        THEY WERE IN THE TRADES,
        THEY WERE PROFESSIONALS,

743
00:31:47,271 --> 00:31:49,505
       THEY WERE ALMOST ANYTHING
       BUT A FARMER.            

744
00:31:49,573 --> 00:31:52,041
        YOU WEREN'T EVEN ALLOWED
        TO OWN LAND IN RUSSIA   

745
00:31:52,109 --> 00:31:53,709
             IF YOU WERE JEWISH.

746
00:31:53,778 --> 00:31:55,878
             IT WAS ALSO        
             VERY MARGINAL LAND.

747
00:31:55,946 --> 00:31:58,681
            CONNECTICUT POTATOES
            ARE REALLY ROCKS.   

748
00:31:58,749 --> 00:32:02,584
   THIS IS FARMLAND THAT'S BEEN 
   USED HARD FOR OVER 200 YEARS.

749
00:32:02,653 --> 00:32:05,020
         <i> MANY SIMPLY</i>           
      <i> COULDN'T MAKE IT,</i>        

750
00:32:05,089 --> 00:32:08,524
   <i> AND THE OLD YANKEE FARMS</i>    
     <i> KEPT CHANGING HANDS.</i>      

751
00:32:08,592 --> 00:32:11,493
WOW, THAT I WOULD NOT           
HAVE GUESSED.                   

752
00:32:11,562 --> 00:32:13,862
WELL, I GUESS THAT EXPLAINS     
WHY THERE WAS SO MUCH TURNOVER. 

753
00:32:13,931 --> 00:32:15,764
THEY DIDN'T REALLY KNOW         
WHAT THEY WERE DOING            

754
00:32:15,833 --> 00:32:17,433
AND DECIDED TO GIVE UP.         

755
00:32:17,501 --> 00:32:19,435
        <i> BUT THE STORY</i>          
      <i> DOESN'T END THERE.</i>       

756
00:32:19,503 --> 00:32:21,236
     <i> MARY EXPLAINED THAT</i>       
      <i> THE ORGANIZATIONS</i>        

757
00:32:21,305 --> 00:32:22,905
         <i> THAT HELPED</i>           
        <i> BUY THE FARMS</i>          

758
00:32:22,973 --> 00:32:26,141
<i> REALIZED THE EARLY IMMIGRANTS</i>  
  <i> NEEDED FURTHER ASSISTANCE.</i>   

759
00:32:26,210 --> 00:32:28,377
           THE REAL BREAKTHROUGH
           CAME THROUGH IN 1908 

760
00:32:28,446 --> 00:32:31,046
          WHEN THEY ALSO STARTED
          TO PRODUCE A NEWSPAPER

761
00:32:31,115 --> 00:32:34,149
       IN YIDDISH FOR FARMERS   
       CALLED<i> THE JEWISH FARMER,</i>

762
00:32:34,218 --> 00:32:37,386
     WHICH WAS THE FIRST YIDDISH
     AGRICULTURAL MAGAZINE      

763
00:32:37,455 --> 00:32:38,887
                   IN THE WORLD.

764
00:32:38,956 --> 00:32:41,156
      <i> MARY'S FRIEND AVI</i>        
 <i> HAS AGREED TO HELP TRANSLATE</i>  

765
00:32:41,225 --> 00:32:42,558
     <i> SOME OF THE YIDDISH.</i>      

766
00:32:42,626 --> 00:32:44,226
ALL RIGHT,                      
HELP US OUT HERE.               

767
00:32:44,295 --> 00:32:45,761
           AND THE FIRST ARTICLE
           YOU HAVE             

768
00:32:45,830 --> 00:32:48,063
   IS "HOW TO BEST UNDERSTAND   
   YOUR COW," OR...             

769
00:32:48,132 --> 00:32:50,499
           [ speaks in Yiddish ]

770
00:32:50,568 --> 00:32:52,701
             AND THEN IT GOES ON
             TO SAY IN YIDDISH  

771
00:32:52,770 --> 00:32:54,937
        WHAT EVERY FARMER SHOULD
        KNOW ABOUT THEIR COW.   

772
00:32:55,005 --> 00:33:01,009
         [ speaking in Yiddish ]

773
00:33:01,078 --> 00:33:03,912
        "EVERY JEWISH FARMER    
        WHO HAS EYES HAS NOTICED

774
00:33:03,981 --> 00:33:05,080
                "THAT SOME COWS 
                GIVE MILK BETTER

775
00:33:05,149 --> 00:33:06,982
               AND SOME COWS    
               GIVE MILK WORSE."

776
00:33:07,051 --> 00:33:10,018
WHAT YOU HAVE HERE IS THIS      
HOW-TO GUIDE FOR JEWISH FARMERS,

777
00:33:10,087 --> 00:33:12,387
    EVERYTHING THEY NEED TO KNOW
    HOW TO BE A FARMER,         

778
00:33:12,456 --> 00:33:14,656
             ALL THE BASICS,    
             WRITTEN IN YIDDISH.

779
00:33:14,725 --> 00:33:16,558
MARY, WITH ALL THIS INFORMATION 
FROM<i> THE JEWISH FARMER,</i>         

780
00:33:16,627 --> 00:33:17,860
HOW DID THEY DO?                

781
00:33:17,928 --> 00:33:19,094
        THEY DID GREAT.         

782
00:33:19,163 --> 00:33:21,730
      IN 1908, IT ONLY HAD      
      638 SUBSCRIBERS,          

783
00:33:21,799 --> 00:33:24,099
     AND FIVE YEARS LATER,      
     IT HAD THOUSANDS.          

784
00:33:24,168 --> 00:33:27,135
 IN CONNECTICUT, JEWISH FARMERS 
 DEVELOPED A NICHE MARKET       

785
00:33:27,204 --> 00:33:29,972
    FOR THINGS LIKE TOBACCO,    
    POULTRY, EGGS, DAIRY,       

786
00:33:30,040 --> 00:33:32,274
   AND SECOND AND THIRD         
   GENERATION JEWISH FARMERS    

787
00:33:32,343 --> 00:33:33,675
       REALLY PROSPERED.        

788
00:33:33,744 --> 00:33:35,344
           YOU KNOW, SOME PEOPLE
           DIDN'T MAKE IT       

789
00:33:35,412 --> 00:33:36,812
              AND THEY WENT BACK
              TO THE CITY,      

790
00:33:36,881 --> 00:33:38,180
                BUT OTHER PEOPLE
                WERE SMART      

791
00:33:38,249 --> 00:33:40,115
       AND THEY FOUND OTHER WAYS
       TO MAKE MONEY,           

792
00:33:40,184 --> 00:33:42,918
     AND THEY TURNED THEIR FARMS
     INTO EITHER BOARDING HOUSES

793
00:33:42,987 --> 00:33:44,553
             OR WEEKEND RESORTS,

794
00:33:44,622 --> 00:33:46,388
               SO MUCH SO,      
               THAT AT ONE TIME,

795
00:33:46,457 --> 00:33:48,824
   THIS AREA WAS CALLED         
   THE CATSKILLS OF NEW ENGLAND.

796
00:33:48,893 --> 00:33:51,727
THE IDEA THAT THIS HOUSE        
WAS MORE THAN A HOUSE,          

797
00:33:51,795 --> 00:33:54,363
THAT IT COULD HAVE BEEN         
A SANCTUARY FOR PEOPLE,         

798
00:33:54,431 --> 00:33:56,398
I MEAN, THAT'S                  
JUST FANTASTIC.                 

799
00:33:56,467 --> 00:33:58,300
WELL, IT WAS A GREAT EXPERIENCE,
AND THANK YOU VERY MUCH.        

800
00:33:58,369 --> 00:33:59,701
THANK YOU.                      

801
00:33:59,770 --> 00:34:01,837
   FOR MORE OF MY INTERVIEW     
      WITH DANIEL SAWYER,       

802
00:34:01,906 --> 00:34:07,476
   VISIT<i> HISTORY DETECTIVES</i>     
     ON THE WEB AT pbs.org.     

803
00:34:07,544 --> 00:34:10,245
   THE TOWN OF WILLIAMSBURG     
    IN BROOKLYN, NEW YORK,      

804
00:34:10,314 --> 00:34:12,681
      ALSO SAW AN INFLUX        
      OF JEWISH RESIDENTS       

805
00:34:12,750 --> 00:34:14,583
        AT THE TURN OF          
       THE 20th CENTURY         

806
00:34:14,652 --> 00:34:18,787
 THANKS TO AN INCREDIBLE FEAT   
   OF AMERICAN ENGINEERING.     

807
00:34:18,856 --> 00:34:21,757
        CONSTRUCTION ON         
   THE WILLIAMSBURG BRIDGE,     

808
00:34:21,825 --> 00:34:24,226
       NEW YORK'S SECOND        
   GREAT SUSPENSION BRIDGE,     

809
00:34:24,295 --> 00:34:27,496
           BEGAN ON             
      NOVEMBER 7th, 1896.       

810
00:34:27,564 --> 00:34:29,431
   TO ALLEVIATE THE TRAFFIC     

811
00:34:29,500 --> 00:34:31,300
         OVERWHELMING           
     THE BROOKLYN BRIDGE,       

812
00:34:31,368 --> 00:34:33,769
     ITS DESIGN CALLED FOR      
    A DOUBLE-DECKER ROADWAY     

813
00:34:33,837 --> 00:34:37,005
   FOR CARRIAGES, TROLLEYS,     
       AND PEDESTRIANS.         

814
00:34:37,074 --> 00:34:40,008
      IN ORDER TO SUPPORT       
    TWO LEVELS OF TRAFFIC,      

815
00:34:40,077 --> 00:34:43,478
     310-FOOT-HIGH TOWERS       
         WERE ERECTED,          

816
00:34:43,547 --> 00:34:46,481
      THE FIRST EVER MADE       
      ENTIRELY OF STEEL.        

817
00:34:46,550 --> 00:34:48,917
    BUILT IN HALF THE TIME      
    OF THE BROOKLYN BRIDGE      

818
00:34:48,986 --> 00:34:51,453
 AND MEASURING FOUR AND A HALF  
         FEET LONGER,           

819
00:34:51,522 --> 00:34:53,789
    THE WILLIAMSBURG BRIDGE     
        STOLE THE TITLE         

820
00:34:53,857 --> 00:34:56,425
   OF THE LONGEST SUSPENSION    
      BRIDGE IN THE WORLD       

821
00:34:56,493 --> 00:35:00,295
       WHEN IT OPENED ON        
      DECEMBER 19, 1903.        

822
00:35:00,364 --> 00:35:03,665
JEWISH RESIDENTS OF MANHATTAN'S 
  CROWDED EAST SIDE TENEMENTS   

823
00:35:03,734 --> 00:35:06,468
      STREAMED OVER THIS        
    STATE-OF-THE-ART BRIDGE     

824
00:35:06,537 --> 00:35:09,604
       TO FIND NEW HOMES        
     IN SPACIOUS BROOKLYN.      

825
00:35:09,673 --> 00:35:12,841
      THE BRAND-NEW LINK        
BETWEEN THE THEN-SEPARATE CITIES

826
00:35:12,910 --> 00:35:15,010
   OF NEW YORK AND BROOKLYN     

827
00:35:15,079 --> 00:35:17,345
         ALSO PROVIDED          
        A FINAL IMPETUS         

828
00:35:17,414 --> 00:35:19,247
   FOR THEM TO CONSOLIDATE.     

829
00:35:19,316 --> 00:35:21,983
           IN 1898,             
   THEY JOINED WITH QUEENS,     

830
00:35:22,052 --> 00:35:23,985
        STATEN ISLAND,          
         AND THE BRONX          

831
00:35:24,054 --> 00:35:28,757
TO BECOME THE SINGLE UNITED CITY
         OF NEW YORK.           

832
00:35:33,831 --> 00:35:36,098
            Tukufu:             
 <i> OUR LAST STORY INVESTIGATES</i>   
        <i> THE CONNECTION</i>         

833
00:35:36,166 --> 00:35:40,502
 <i> BETWEEN A PORTRAIT, A POET,</i>   
  <i> AND THE FALL OF AN EMPIRE.</i>   

834
00:35:43,941 --> 00:35:47,843
  <i> IN 1923, THE LEBANESE-BORN</i>   
      <i> POET KHALIL GIBRAN</i>       

835
00:35:47,911 --> 00:35:50,212
    <i> PUBLISHES</i> THE PROPHET,     

836
00:35:50,280 --> 00:35:52,013
    <i> A COLLECTION OF POEMS</i>      
   <i> EXPLORING FACETS OF LIFE</i>    

837
00:35:52,082 --> 00:35:54,416
   <i> AND THE HUMAN CONDITION.</i>    

838
00:35:54,485 --> 00:35:56,718
 <i> ALTHOUGH VIEWED SKEPTICALLY</i>   
         <i> BY CRITICS,</i>           

839
00:35:56,787 --> 00:35:58,653
        <i> IT WILL BECOME</i>         
    <i> A LITERARY SENSATION,</i>      

840
00:35:58,722 --> 00:36:02,824
 <i> MAKING KHALIL GIBRAN ONE OF</i>   
<i> THE WORLD'S BESTSELLING POETS</i>  

841
00:36:02,893 --> 00:36:04,693
          <i> AND HAVING</i>           
      <i> A POWERFUL IMPACT</i>        

842
00:36:04,761 --> 00:36:08,897
 <i> ON THE COUNTERCULTURE OF THE</i>  
<i> 1960s AND THE NEW-AGE MOVEMENT.</i>

843
00:36:08,966 --> 00:36:11,266
     <i> BUT MANY ARE UNAWARE</i>      
       <i> THAT THE WRITER</i>         

844
00:36:11,335 --> 00:36:13,135
           <i> WAS ALSO</i>            
     <i> A PROLIFIC PAINTER,</i>       

845
00:36:13,203 --> 00:36:15,537
    <i> CAPTURING CELEBRITIES</i>      
      <i> AND FAMOUS FIGURES</i>       

846
00:36:15,606 --> 00:36:18,607
     <i> OF THE 20th CENTURY</i>       
          <i> ON CANVAS.</i>           

847
00:36:18,675 --> 00:36:22,277
  <i> NOW, ALMOST EIGHT DECADES</i>    
    <i> AFTER GIBRAN'S DEATH,</i>      

848
00:36:22,346 --> 00:36:27,349
 <i> BOB DIAB FROM OVERLAND PARK,</i>  
    <i> KANSAS, HAS A PORTRAIT</i>     

849
00:36:27,417 --> 00:36:30,285
 <i> THAT HE THINKS MAY HAVE BEEN</i>  
      <i> PAINTED BY GIBRAN.</i>       

850
00:36:32,589 --> 00:36:35,056
      [ doorbell rings ]        

851
00:36:35,125 --> 00:36:35,924
              HELLO, I'M TUKUFU.

852
00:36:35,993 --> 00:36:37,759
I'M BOB.                        
PLEASE COME IN.                 

853
00:36:37,828 --> 00:36:39,261
WOW, SO WHAT IS THIS?           

854
00:36:39,329 --> 00:36:43,031
         THIS IS MY GRANDFATHER,
         NAJEEB MUSA DIAB.      

855
00:36:43,100 --> 00:36:46,368
          HE WAS A PUBLISHER    
          OF AN ARABIC NEWSPAPER

856
00:36:46,436 --> 00:36:49,271
     IN BROOKLYN, NEW YORK,     
     AT THE TURN OF THE CENTURY.

857
00:36:49,339 --> 00:36:52,374
   JUST AFTER HE IMMIGRATED HERE
   FROM SYRIA.                  

858
00:36:52,442 --> 00:36:53,975
AND WHICH PAPER                 
WAS THAT?                       

859
00:36:54,044 --> 00:36:55,844
        IT WAS CALLED           
        <i> THE MIRROR OF THE WEST.</i>

860
00:36:55,913 --> 00:36:57,746
         <i> BOB SAYS HIS</i>          
   <i> GRANDFATHER'S NEWSPAPER</i>     

861
00:36:57,814 --> 00:37:00,549
<i> WAS ONCE AN IMPORTANT RESOURCE</i> 
     <i> FOR ARAB IMMIGRANTS,</i>      

862
00:37:00,617 --> 00:37:03,451
       <i> A FAMILIAR VOICE</i>        
 <i> REPORTING ON CHANGING EVENTS</i>  

863
00:37:03,520 --> 00:37:05,320
   <i> IN THEIR HOME COUNTRIES</i>     

864
00:37:05,389 --> 00:37:07,756
      <i> AND ON LIFE WITHIN</i>       
  <i> ARAB IMMIGRANT COMMUNITIES</i>   

865
00:37:07,824 --> 00:37:09,491
    <i> IN THE UNITED STATES.</i>      

866
00:37:09,560 --> 00:37:11,993
 <i> HE PUBLISHED GIBRAN'S POEMS</i>   
      <i> IN HIS NEWSPAPER,</i>        

867
00:37:12,062 --> 00:37:14,229
       <i> GIVING THE POET</i>         
      <i> A PROMINENT VOICE</i>        

868
00:37:14,298 --> 00:37:16,531
       <i> IN THE ISOLATED</i>         
       <i> ARAB COMMUNITY.</i>         

869
00:37:16,600 --> 00:37:20,468
WHAT IS IT ABOUT THIS PAINTING  
THAT'S SO IMPORTANT?            

870
00:37:20,537 --> 00:37:23,638
   THE STORY IS THAT IT         
   WAS PAINTED BY KHALIL GIBRAN.

871
00:37:23,707 --> 00:37:26,241
NOW, I KNOW OF HIM              
AS A VERY FAMOUS WRITER,        

872
00:37:26,310 --> 00:37:27,943
BUT I DIDN'T KNOW               
HE DID PAINTINGS.               

873
00:37:28,011 --> 00:37:29,110
                      YES.      

874
00:37:29,179 --> 00:37:30,512
ESPECIALLY PORTRAITS.           
                      YES.      

875
00:37:30,581 --> 00:37:32,013
           AND I KNOW THAT HE...

876
00:37:32,082 --> 00:37:34,849
    <i> BOB TELLS ME A COUSIN</i>      
 <i> HE HASN'T SEEN IN MANY YEARS</i>  

877
00:37:34,918 --> 00:37:37,919
      <i> ONCE HAD A DRAWING</i>       
     <i> SIGNED BY THE POET.</i>       

878
00:37:37,988 --> 00:37:40,055
    <i> ALTHOUGH THE PAINTING</i>      
     <i> OF BOB'S GRANDFATHER</i>      

879
00:37:40,123 --> 00:37:43,391
   <i> IS NOT SIGNED, THERE ARE</i>    
    <i> SOME POTENTIAL CLUES.</i>      

880
00:37:43,460 --> 00:37:45,493
WHAT IS THIS MEDAL HERE,        
DO YOU KNOW WHAT THAT'S ABOUT?  

881
00:37:45,562 --> 00:37:47,028
                  I DO NOT KNOW.

882
00:37:47,097 --> 00:37:49,664
AND THIS HERE,                  
THIS IS A WATCH, RIGHT?         

883
00:37:49,733 --> 00:37:52,300
     <i> BOB HAS A TIMEPIECE</i>       
  <i> THAT HAS BEEN PASSED DOWN</i>    

884
00:37:52,369 --> 00:37:54,569
      <i> THROUGH HIS FAMILY</i>       
    <i> WHICH HE THINKS MAY BE</i>     

885
00:37:54,638 --> 00:37:56,504
        <i> THE SAME WATCH</i>         
       <i> IN THE PAINTING.</i>        

886
00:37:56,573 --> 00:37:59,474
     THIS POCKET WATCH WAS      
     PRESENTED TO MY GRANDFATHER

887
00:37:59,543 --> 00:38:02,410
       WHEN HE WAS PRESIDENT OF 
       THE UNITED SYRIAN SOCIETY

888
00:38:02,479 --> 00:38:04,813
                IN 1914 TO 1915.

889
00:38:04,881 --> 00:38:06,848
FINE TIMEPIECE.                 
                      THANK YOU.

890
00:38:06,917 --> 00:38:09,384
    <i> BOB SAYS THAT ALTHOUGH</i>     
       <i> HIS GRANDFATHER</i>         

891
00:38:09,453 --> 00:38:11,119
        <i> IMMIGRATED TO</i>          
      <i> THE UNITED STATES,</i>       

892
00:38:11,188 --> 00:38:13,888
     <i> HE DEVOTED HIS LIFE</i>       
 <i> TO THE CAUSE OF INDEPENDENCE</i>  

893
00:38:13,957 --> 00:38:15,957
    <i> FOR SYRIA AND LEBANON.</i>     

894
00:38:16,026 --> 00:38:18,193
     <i> BOTH WERE STILL PART</i>      
    <i> OF THE OTTOMAN EMPIRE,</i>     

895
00:38:18,261 --> 00:38:21,062
 <i> WHICH HAD RULED THOSE LANDS</i>   
  <i> FOR SEVERAL HUNDRED YEARS.</i>   

896
00:38:21,131 --> 00:38:23,031
SO WHAT DO YOU WANT ME          
TO FIND OUT FOR YOU?            

897
00:38:23,100 --> 00:38:26,668
        WELL, COULD IT HAVE BEEN
        PAINTED BY KHALIL GIBRAN

898
00:38:26,737 --> 00:38:30,138
           AND ANY BACKGROUND   
           ABOUT MY GRANDFATHER.

899
00:38:30,207 --> 00:38:32,540
  <i> THE PORTRAIT IS TOO LARGE</i>    
      <i> TO CARRY WITH ME,</i>        

900
00:38:32,609 --> 00:38:36,044
     <i> SO I'M GOING TO TAKE</i>      
         <i> SOME PHOTOS.</i>          

901
00:38:36,113 --> 00:38:39,114
     <i> I READ KHALIL GIBRAN</i>      
         <i> IN COLLEGE,</i>           

902
00:38:39,182 --> 00:38:42,117
    <i> BUT I DON'T KNOW MUCH</i>      
      <i> ABOUT HIS ARTWORK.</i>       

903
00:38:42,185 --> 00:38:45,787
  <i> I'M HEADING INTO BROOKLYN,</i>   
  <i> NEW YORK, HOME TO A LARGE</i>    

904
00:38:45,856 --> 00:38:48,590
      <i> AND LONG-STANDING</i>        
   <i> ARAB-AMERICAN COMMUNITY,</i>    

905
00:38:48,658 --> 00:38:51,659
    <i> TO SHOW BOB'S PAINTING</i>     
 <i> TO A KHALIL GIBRAN SCHOLAR,</i>   

906
00:38:51,728 --> 00:38:53,461
       <i> GREGORY ORFALEA.</i>        

907
00:38:53,530 --> 00:38:55,130
WELCOME.                        

908
00:38:55,198 --> 00:38:58,066
  <i> GREG SAYS MUCH OF GIBRAN'S</i>   
     <i> WRITING AND PAINTING</i>      

909
00:38:58,135 --> 00:39:00,502
    <i> REFLECTS HIS IDENTITY</i>      
       <i> AS AN IMMIGRANT</i>         

910
00:39:00,570 --> 00:39:02,237
      <i> IN A FOREIGN LAND.</i>       

911
00:39:02,305 --> 00:39:05,006
I THINK HIS EXPERIENCE          
IN AMERICA                      

912
00:39:05,075 --> 00:39:07,142
WAS ONE OF ALIENATION.          

913
00:39:07,210 --> 00:39:09,544
IT WAS A LONELY EXPERIENCE      
LINGUISTICALLY.                 

914
00:39:09,613 --> 00:39:11,079
HE DIDN'T KNOW ENGLISH.         

915
00:39:11,148 --> 00:39:15,316
HE WAS NOT IN BEAUTIFUL,        
VERDANT, SNOWY MT. LEBANON,     

916
00:39:15,385 --> 00:39:18,787
HE WAS LIVING IN THE TENEMENTS  
IN GRIMY BOSTON,                

917
00:39:18,855 --> 00:39:21,222
SOUTH BOSTON,                   
WEST ROXBURY.                   

918
00:39:21,291 --> 00:39:26,094
  <i> GREG EXPLAINS THAT GIBRAN</i>    
  <i> ARRIVED IN BOSTON IN 1895</i>    

919
00:39:26,163 --> 00:39:28,329
      <i> AT THE AGE OF 12.</i>        

920
00:39:28,398 --> 00:39:31,399
     <i> HIS FAMILY WAS PART</i>       
    <i> OF AN ENORMOUS INFLUX</i>      

921
00:39:31,468 --> 00:39:33,835
  <i> OF MOSTLY POOR IMMIGRANTS</i>    
         <i> WHO ARRIVED</i>           

922
00:39:33,904 --> 00:39:36,271
  <i> AT THE TURN OF THE CENTURY</i>   
    <i> FROM LEBANON AND SYRIA</i>     

923
00:39:36,339 --> 00:39:38,473
      <i> TO PLACES SUCH AS</i>        
     <i> BROOKLYN, NEW YORK,</i>       

924
00:39:38,542 --> 00:39:40,141
      <i> AND SOUTH BOSTON.</i>        

925
00:39:40,210 --> 00:39:42,343
       <i> HIS FIRST POETRY</i>        
        <i> WAS IN ARABIC</i>          

926
00:39:42,412 --> 00:39:44,879
  <i> AND OFTEN ADDRESSED YOUNG</i>    
   <i> IMMIGRANTS LIKE HIMSELF</i>     

927
00:39:44,948 --> 00:39:47,982
 <i> STRUGGLING TO FIND THEIR WAY</i>  
    <i> IN THE UNITED STATES.</i>      

928
00:39:48,051 --> 00:39:51,486
HE WROTE POEMS                  
TO TELL YOUNG SYRIAN AMERICANS  

929
00:39:51,555 --> 00:39:53,855
TO BE PROUD OF THEIR HERITAGE   
IN THE UNITED STATES            

930
00:39:53,924 --> 00:39:58,026
AND FEEL THAT THEY HAD          
SOMETHING TO GIVE OF MAGNITUDE. 

931
00:39:58,094 --> 00:40:00,595
    <i> IN 1923, HE PUBLISHED</i>      
         <i> A COLLECTION</i>          

932
00:40:00,664 --> 00:40:03,131
  <i> OF 26 ENGLISH PROSE POEMS</i>    

933
00:40:03,200 --> 00:40:06,968
  <i> ABOUT A MYSTICAL SPIRITUAL</i>   
     <i> LEADER,</i> THE PROPHET.      

934
00:40:07,037 --> 00:40:11,739
<i> IN IT, GIBRAN EXPLORED SUBJECTS</i>
<i> LIKE LOVE, BEAUTY, AND GIVING.</i> 

935
00:40:11,808 --> 00:40:14,676
  <i> "YOU GIVE BUT LITTLE WHEN</i>    
<i> YOU GIVE OF YOUR POSSESSIONS.</i>  

936
00:40:14,744 --> 00:40:18,479
<i> IT IS WHEN YOU GIVE OF YOURSELF</i>
    <i> THAT YOU TRULY GIVE."</i>      

937
00:40:18,548 --> 00:40:21,649
   <i> THE UNIQUE BLEND OF EAST</i>    
      <i> AND WEST THINKING</i>        

938
00:40:21,718 --> 00:40:24,419
      <i> HAS SOLD MILLIONS</i>        
          <i> OF COPIES.</i>           

939
00:40:24,487 --> 00:40:26,321
THERE ARE SOME PARTS            
OF<i> THE PROPHET</i>                  

940
00:40:26,389 --> 00:40:27,855
THAT ARE VERY INTERESTING,      

941
00:40:27,924 --> 00:40:30,024
AND SOME OF THE APHORISMS       
THAT ARE DIFFERENT.             

942
00:40:30,093 --> 00:40:32,060
"WORK IS LOVE MADE VISIBLE."    

943
00:40:32,128 --> 00:40:34,696
IT WAS A COMPLETELY DIFFERENT   
STYLE OF WRITING                

944
00:40:34,764 --> 00:40:38,967
THAN WAS GOING ON RIGHT THEN    
AND THERE WITH THE AMERICANS.   

945
00:40:39,035 --> 00:40:41,202
   <i> BUT GREG BELIEVES THAT,</i>     
         <i> IRONICALLY,</i>           

946
00:40:41,271 --> 00:40:44,505
   THE PROPHET'S<i> COMMERCIAL</i>     
 <i> SUCCESS MAY HAVE CONTRIBUTED</i>  

947
00:40:44,574 --> 00:40:47,442
  <i> TO GIBRAN'S MIXED REVIEWS</i>    
        <i> FROM CRITICS.</i>          

948
00:40:47,510 --> 00:40:51,346
AND ALSO YOU HAVE TO SAY        
THAT ANOTHER REASON WAS         

949
00:40:51,414 --> 00:40:53,848
THAT THEY JUST SIMPLY           
DID NOT TRANSLATE               

950
00:40:53,917 --> 00:40:58,152
HIS TOUGHER, MORE REBELLIOUS,   
PRINCIPLED POLITICAL WORK       

951
00:40:58,221 --> 00:41:01,189
THAT WAS PUBLISHED              
PRIOR TO<i> THE PROPHET.</i>           

952
00:41:01,257 --> 00:41:03,625
WE TRANSLATED A POEM OF HIS     
THAT HAD NEVER SEEN ENGLISH,    

953
00:41:03,693 --> 00:41:05,393
"DEFEAT, MY DEFEAT."            

954
00:41:05,462 --> 00:41:07,462
THAT MATERIAL SHOWS             
A MORE POLITICAL,               

955
00:41:07,530 --> 00:41:13,067
MORE DEFIANT,                   
MORE SOCIALLY ENGAGED GIBRAN.   

956
00:41:13,136 --> 00:41:15,603
I'LL READ JUST A BIT            
OF IT.                          

957
00:41:15,672 --> 00:41:20,541
"DEFEAT, MY DEFEAT,             
MY SHINING SWORD AND SHIELD.    

958
00:41:20,610 --> 00:41:23,144
"IN YOUR EYES I HAVE READ       

959
00:41:23,213 --> 00:41:26,414
"THAT TO BE ENTHRONED           
IS TO BE ENSLAVED,              

960
00:41:26,483 --> 00:41:29,450
"AND WE SHALL STAND             
IN THE SUN WITH A WILL          

961
00:41:29,519 --> 00:41:32,186
AND WE SHALL BE DANGEROUS."     

962
00:41:32,255 --> 00:41:34,922
SALMA JAYYUSI,                  
THE PALESTINIAN CRITIC,         

963
00:41:34,991 --> 00:41:37,892
SAYS THAT HE IS THE MOST        
IMPORTANT LITERARY FIGURE       

964
00:41:37,961 --> 00:41:40,962
IN THE ARAB WORLD IN THE FIRST  
HALF OF THE 20th CENTURY.       

965
00:41:41,031 --> 00:41:42,864
THAT'S BIG.                     

966
00:41:42,932 --> 00:41:45,933
      <i> I TELL GREG ABOUT</i>        
      <i> MY INVESTIGATION.</i>        

967
00:41:46,002 --> 00:41:48,936
  SO I'M PARTICULARLY INTERESTED
  IN THE RELATIONSHIP           

968
00:41:49,005 --> 00:41:52,807
           BETWEEN KHALIL GIBRAN
           AND NAJEEB DIAB.     

969
00:41:52,876 --> 00:41:55,710
        CAN YOU TALK TO ME      
        A LITTLE BIT ABOUT DIAB?

970
00:41:55,779 --> 00:41:59,380
WELL, HE WAS A LEADER OF        
THE COMMUNITY AS A JOURNALIST.  

971
00:41:59,449 --> 00:42:02,917
HE WAS A LEADER OF              
THE UNITED SYRIAN SOCIETY.      

972
00:42:02,986 --> 00:42:06,721
IT WAS FOR FREEDOM              
FOR SYRIA FROM OTTOMAN TURKEY.  

973
00:42:06,790 --> 00:42:09,424
HE WAS                          
A HIGHLY RESPECTED MAN.         

974
00:42:09,492 --> 00:42:12,059
    <i> GREG CONFIRMS BOTH MEN</i>     
       <i> KNEW EACH OTHER</i>         

975
00:42:12,128 --> 00:42:14,028
          <i> AND MOVED</i>            
     <i> IN SIMILAR CIRCLES,</i>       

976
00:42:14,097 --> 00:42:16,030
    <i> EACH SPEAKING IN FAVOR</i>     
       <i> OF INDEPENDENCE</i>         

977
00:42:16,099 --> 00:42:18,032
    <i> FOR SYRIA AND LEBANON.</i>     

978
00:42:18,101 --> 00:42:22,069
   <i> LIKE GIBRAN, NAJEEB DIAB</i>    
  <i> WAS PROFOUNDLY INFLUENCED</i>    

979
00:42:22,138 --> 00:42:26,574
<i> BY AMERICAN IDEAS OF POLITICAL</i> 
   <i> LIBERTY AND FREE SPEECH.</i>    

980
00:42:26,643 --> 00:42:28,876
THESE PEOPLE HAD                
COME TO AMERICA,                

981
00:42:28,945 --> 00:42:32,880
THEY HAD TASTED THE FRUITS      
OF DEMOCRACY AND SECULARISM.    

982
00:42:32,949 --> 00:42:35,750
MOST OF THEM LIKED              
WHAT THEY SAW                   

983
00:42:35,819 --> 00:42:37,485
AND LIKED WHAT THEY TASTED.     

984
00:42:37,554 --> 00:42:39,854
THEY WANTED TO SEE IT           
IN THEIR HOME COUNTRIES.        

985
00:42:39,923 --> 00:42:43,157
     <i> BUT GREG'S NOT SURE</i>       
 <i> IF GIBRAN EVER PAINTED THIS.</i>  

986
00:42:43,226 --> 00:42:47,028
IT'S ALMOST TOO REALISTIC.      

987
00:42:47,096 --> 00:42:52,500
THERE'S NO PRE-RAPHAELITE LIGHT 
AND MISTINESS ABOUT IT          

988
00:42:52,569 --> 00:42:55,002
THAT YOU SAW                    
IN GIBRAN'S PAINTINGS.          

989
00:42:55,071 --> 00:42:57,405
     <i> HE SAYS THE LARGEST</i>       
      <i> PUBLIC COLLECTION</i>        

990
00:42:57,473 --> 00:42:59,507
     <i> OF GIBRAN PAINTINGS</i>       
         <i> IN THE U.S.</i>           

991
00:42:59,576 --> 00:43:02,410
   <i> IS AT THE TELFAIR MUSEUM</i>    
    <i> IN SAVANNAH, GEORGIA,</i>      

992
00:43:02,478 --> 00:43:04,712
       <i> SO I'M ARRANGING</i>        
    <i> TO HAVE BOB'S PORTRAIT</i>     

993
00:43:04,781 --> 00:43:07,081
        <i> SHIPPED THERE</i>          
       <i> FOR COMPARISON.</i>         

994
00:43:07,150 --> 00:43:10,551
 <i> MEANWHILE, I'M GOING TO TRY</i>   
 <i> TO TRACK DOWN BOB'S COUSIN,</i>   

995
00:43:10,620 --> 00:43:17,024
 <i> WHOM HE HAD SAID ONCE OWNED</i>   
  <i> ARTWORK SIGNED BY GIBRAN.</i>    

996
00:43:17,093 --> 00:43:19,760
     <i> EVENTUALLY, I LOCATE</i>      
         <i> ROBERT MADEY</i>          

997
00:43:19,829 --> 00:43:22,430
        <i> ON LONG ISLAND</i>         
     <i> NEAR NEW YORK CITY.</i>       

998
00:43:22,498 --> 00:43:25,366
  <i> ROBERT IS ALSO A GRANDSON</i>    
<i> OF THE MAN IN BOB'S PORTRAIT,</i>  

999
00:43:25,435 --> 00:43:27,134
         <i> NAJEEB DIAB.</i>          

1000
00:43:27,203 --> 00:43:29,070
WELCOME.                        
            THANK YOU VERY MUCH.

1001
00:43:29,138 --> 00:43:33,174
NOW, IT'S MY UNDERSTANDING      
THAT YOU ACTUALLY HAVE A SKETCH 

1002
00:43:33,243 --> 00:43:37,678
THAT KHALIL GIBRAN              
DID AND SIGNED.                 

1003
00:43:37,747 --> 00:43:39,814
             I DO, AND AS       
             A MATTER OF FACT...

1004
00:43:39,882 --> 00:43:42,683
       <i> ROBERT SHOWS ME</i>         
<i> THE SKETCH OF HIS AUNT SELMA.</i>  

1005
00:43:42,752 --> 00:43:45,353
  <i> THE WOMAN IS NAJEEB DIAB'S</i>   
          <i> DAUGHTER.</i>            

1006
00:43:45,421 --> 00:43:47,989
    <i> HE SAYS THAT ALTHOUGH</i>      
 <i> THE ORIGINAL HAS BEEN SOLD,</i>   

1007
00:43:48,057 --> 00:43:50,324
       <i> THERE'S NO DOUBT</i>        
         <i> WHO DREW IT.</i>          

1008
00:43:50,393 --> 00:43:54,395
          "MY LOVE TO SELMA DIAB
          FROM GIBRAN GIBRAN."  

1009
00:43:54,464 --> 00:43:57,098
WOW, VERY,                      
VERY INTERESTING.               

1010
00:43:57,166 --> 00:44:00,167
 WELL, GIBRAN AND MY GRANDFATHER
 WERE FRIENDS.                  

1011
00:44:00,236 --> 00:44:02,770
       <i> ROBERT EXPLAINS</i>         
      <i> THAT KHALIL GIBRAN</i>       

1012
00:44:02,839 --> 00:44:04,972
       <i> WAS CLOSE TO HIS</i>        
        <i> ENTIRE FAMILY,</i>         

1013
00:44:05,041 --> 00:44:07,508
      <i> SHARING POLITICAL</i>        
   <i> AND ARTISTIC INTERESTS.</i>     

1014
00:44:07,577 --> 00:44:11,812
 THEY WERE FOUNDERS OF A SOCIETY
 CALLED AL-RABITAH,             

1015
00:44:11,881 --> 00:44:14,982
           AND THAT ORGANIZATION
           WAS FORMED TO PROMOTE

1016
00:44:15,051 --> 00:44:19,086
     AND PERPETUATE THE         
     ARABIC LANGUAGE AND CULTURE

1017
00:44:19,155 --> 00:44:21,255
                AND LITERATURE  
                IN THIS COUNTRY.

1018
00:44:21,324 --> 00:44:25,926
    AND MY FATHER, IN FACT,     
    DELIVERED A EULOGY TO GIBRAN

1019
00:44:25,995 --> 00:44:27,928
            WHEN HE PASSED AWAY.

1020
00:44:27,997 --> 00:44:31,265
I'M DOING AN INVESTIGATION      
TO FIND OUT                     

1021
00:44:31,334 --> 00:44:35,870
IF KHALIL GIBRAN COULD HAVE     
ACTUALLY PAINTED THIS PORTRAIT. 

1022
00:44:35,938 --> 00:44:37,672
HAVE YOU EVER                   
SEEN THIS BEFORE?               

1023
00:44:37,740 --> 00:44:38,939
                         I HAVE.

1024
00:44:39,008 --> 00:44:40,941
       I HAVE THE ORIGINAL PHOTO

1025
00:44:41,010 --> 00:44:44,111
        FROM WHICH THIS PORTRAIT
        WAS PAINTED.            

1026
00:44:44,180 --> 00:44:45,613
THIS IS AMAZING.                

1027
00:44:45,682 --> 00:44:48,382
THE TWIST IN THE HAIR           
IS AT THE EXACT SAME PLACE,     

1028
00:44:48,451 --> 00:44:51,285
THE TIE IS THE SAME,            
THE COAT IS THE SAME,           

1029
00:44:51,354 --> 00:44:53,354
THE NUMBER OF BUTTONS           
ARE THE SAME.                   

1030
00:44:53,423 --> 00:44:55,623
DO YOU KNOW WHEN                
THIS PHOTOGRAPH WAS TAKEN?      

1031
00:44:55,692 --> 00:44:59,493
     NO, BUT I THINK IT WAS DONE
     PROBABLY IN CONNECTION     

1032
00:44:59,562 --> 00:45:03,998
   WITH A CONFERENCE HE ATTENDED
   IN PARIS IN 1913.            

1033
00:45:04,067 --> 00:45:06,667
    IT MAY HAVE BEEN DONE JUST  
    PRIOR TO OR JUST AFTERWARDS.

1034
00:45:06,736 --> 00:45:09,470
 <i> ROBERT SAYS HIS GRANDFATHER</i>   
           <i> ATTENDED</i>            

1035
00:45:09,539 --> 00:45:13,307
 <i> A MAJOR CONFERENCE IN PARIS</i>   
   <i> JUST BEFORE WORLD WAR I</i>     

1036
00:45:13,376 --> 00:45:16,744
        <i> AS THE HEAD OF</i>         
  <i> THE UNITED SYRIAN SOCIETY.</i>   

1037
00:45:16,813 --> 00:45:19,780
 <i> DELEGATES FROM ARAB NATIONS</i>   
  <i> AND OTHER IMMIGRANT GROUPS</i>   

1038
00:45:19,849 --> 00:45:23,084
  <i> WERE DEBATING THE BEST WAY</i>   
    <i> OF ENDING TURKISH RULE</i>     

1039
00:45:23,152 --> 00:45:25,386
    <i> IN SYRIA AND LEBANON.</i>      

1040
00:45:25,455 --> 00:45:27,254
   <i> THE WATCH BOB SHOWED ME</i>     

1041
00:45:27,323 --> 00:45:29,824
        <i> WAS ALSO FROM</i>          
  <i> THE UNITED SYRIAN SOCIETY</i>    

1042
00:45:29,892 --> 00:45:33,360
<i> AND MAY WELL BE THE SAME WATCH</i> 
       <i> IN THE PORTRAIT.</i>        

1043
00:45:33,429 --> 00:45:36,063
      <i> HAD GIBRAN PAINTED</i>       
   <i> THIS IMAGE OF HIS FRIEND</i>    

1044
00:45:36,132 --> 00:45:39,166
        <i> TO COMMEMORATE</i>         
    <i> THIS IMPORTANT MOMENT?</i>     

1045
00:45:39,235 --> 00:45:42,269
 <i> BOB'S SKEPTICAL THE PAINTING</i>  
    <i> WAS DONE BY GIBRAN --</i>      

1046
00:45:42,338 --> 00:45:45,439
  <i> THE STYLE IS SO DIFFERENT</i>    
<i> FROM THE IMAGE OF HIS AUNT --</i>  

1047
00:45:45,508 --> 00:45:47,541
   <i> BUT HE CAN'T BE CERTAIN.</i>    

1048
00:45:47,610 --> 00:45:53,714
        IT'S CONCEIVABLE THAT   
        HE COULD'VE DONE A COPY.

1049
00:45:53,783 --> 00:45:56,650
  <i> BOB'S PAINTING HAS ARRIVED</i>   
    <i> AT THE TELFAIR MUSEUM,</i>     

1050
00:45:56,719 --> 00:45:59,887
  <i> WHERE I'M MEETING CURATOR</i>    
        <i> TANIA SAMMONS.</i>         

1051
00:45:59,956 --> 00:46:02,756
WE ARE TRYING TO FIND OUT       

1052
00:46:02,825 --> 00:46:06,961
IF THIS PAINTING                
WAS DONE BY GIBRAN.             

1053
00:46:07,029 --> 00:46:11,332
WELL, KHALIL GIBRAN ACTUALLY WAS
FIRST KNOWN FOR HIS ARTWORK.    

1054
00:46:11,400 --> 00:46:13,467
        <i> TANIA TELLS ME</i>         
     <i> THAT GIBRAN'S TALENT</i>      

1055
00:46:13,536 --> 00:46:15,603
      <i> WON THE ATTENTION</i>        
  <i> OF BOSTON'S ART COMMUNITY</i>    

1056
00:46:15,671 --> 00:46:17,738
      <i> WHILE HE WAS STILL</i>       
           <i> A TEEN.</i>             

1057
00:46:17,807 --> 00:46:20,741
    <i> A SCHOOL HEADMISTRESS</i>      
      <i> NAMED MARY HASKELL</i>       

1058
00:46:20,810 --> 00:46:24,411
      <i> BECAME HIS PATRON</i>        
  <i> AND EVENTUALLY HIS LOVER.</i>    

1059
00:46:24,480 --> 00:46:28,816
  <i> SHE SENT HIM TO STUDY ART</i>    
<i> AT THE ACADEMIE JULIAN IN PARIS</i>

1060
00:46:28,885 --> 00:46:31,952
 <i> AND HAD A PROFOUND INFLUENCE</i>  
         <i> ON HIS LIFE.</i>          

1061
00:46:32,021 --> 00:46:36,257
  IN 1911, SHE HELPED HIM SET UP
  A STUDIO IN NEW YORK CITY.    

1062
00:46:36,325 --> 00:46:39,727
          SHE REALLY ALLOWED HIM
          TO TAKE OFF,          

1063
00:46:39,795 --> 00:46:42,696
             BOTH IN HIS WRITING
             AND VISUAL CAREERS.

1064
00:46:42,765 --> 00:46:45,866
   SO NOT ONLY DID SHE ENCOURAGE
   HIM TO WRITE IN ENGLISH,     

1065
00:46:45,935 --> 00:46:48,335
             BUT SHE HELPED HIM 
             LEARN THE LANGUAGE,

1066
00:46:48,404 --> 00:46:51,005
             SHE EDITED HIS WORK
             AS WELL.           

1067
00:46:51,073 --> 00:46:54,842
NOW, DOES THE LACK OF           
A SIGNATURE TELL US ANYTHING?   

1068
00:46:54,911 --> 00:46:57,344
            KHALIL GIBRAN       
            DID SIGN HIS PIECES,

1069
00:46:57,413 --> 00:46:59,580
                BUT HE DIDN'T   
                SIGN EVERYTHING.

1070
00:46:59,649 --> 00:47:02,283
           HOWEVER, I WOULD SAY 
           THE STYLE OF PAINTING

1071
00:47:02,351 --> 00:47:05,152
              IS NOT TYPICAL    
              FOR KHALIL GIBRAN.

1072
00:47:05,221 --> 00:47:08,289
   <i> TANIA SHOWS ME A SERIES</i>     
   <i> OF PAINTINGS BY GIBRAN,</i>     

1073
00:47:08,357 --> 00:47:11,492
    <i> AND AT FIRST GLIMPSE,</i>      
  <i> HIS WORKS DO NOT RESEMBLE</i>    

1074
00:47:11,560 --> 00:47:13,227
      <i> THE DIAB PORTRAIT.</i>       

1075
00:47:13,296 --> 00:47:15,863
           YOU CAN SEE HOW HE IS
           NOT REALLY FOCUSED   

1076
00:47:15,931 --> 00:47:18,499
      ON THE INDIVIDUAL FEATURES
      OF A PERSON.              

1077
00:47:18,567 --> 00:47:20,701
IT'S VERY FLUID.                
                           YEAH.

1078
00:47:20,770 --> 00:47:25,105
DO YOU HAVE ANY OIL PAINTINGS   
LIKE OURS WHICH ARE A PORTRAIT? 

1079
00:47:25,174 --> 00:47:26,907
       I HAVE A GOOD COMPARISON.

1080
00:47:26,976 --> 00:47:29,176
            IT'S A SELF-PORTRAIT
            OF KHALIL GIBRAN.   

1081
00:47:29,245 --> 00:47:31,011
  <i> THE STYLE OF THIS PORTRAIT</i>   

1082
00:47:31,080 --> 00:47:33,180
   <i> IS ALSO QUITE DIFFERENT</i>     
         <i> FROM BOB'S.</i>           

1083
00:47:33,249 --> 00:47:36,083
          IN THIS PAINTING,     
          GIBRAN'S BRUSH STROKES

1084
00:47:36,152 --> 00:47:38,352
               ARE VERY EVIDENT.

1085
00:47:38,421 --> 00:47:40,020
             THEY'RE MUCH FREER.

1086
00:47:40,089 --> 00:47:43,057
   YOU CAN SEE INDIVIDUAL COLORS
   IN THE PAINTING              

1087
00:47:43,125 --> 00:47:45,826
                AND HIS FACE    
                ISN'T DELINEATED

1088
00:47:45,895 --> 00:47:48,729
                  LIKE THE IMAGE
                  OF MR. DIAB.  

1089
00:47:48,798 --> 00:47:52,032
<i> I EXPLAIN THAT BOB'S PORTRAIT</i>  
   <i> MAY HAVE SOMETHING TO DO</i>    

1090
00:47:52,101 --> 00:47:54,601
  <i> WITH NAJEEB DIAB ATTENDING</i>   
      <i> A MAJOR CONFERENCE</i>       

1091
00:47:54,670 --> 00:47:57,471
      <i> IN PARIS IN 1913.</i>        

1092
00:47:57,540 --> 00:47:59,640
       <i> TANIA SAYS THAT</i>         
     <i> DURING THAT PERIOD,</i>       

1093
00:47:59,709 --> 00:48:02,076
     <i> GIBRAN DID A NUMBER</i>       
  <i> OF PAINTINGS AND DRAWINGS</i>    

1094
00:48:02,144 --> 00:48:04,411
     <i> OF IMPORTANT ARTISTS</i>      
        <i> AND THINKERS.</i>          

1095
00:48:04,480 --> 00:48:06,980
         <i> HE CALLED IT</i>          
 <i> THE "TEMPLE OF ART" SERIES.</i>   

1096
00:48:07,049 --> 00:48:11,585
   CERTAINLY MR. DIAB WOULD HAVE
   FIT WITHIN THAT SERIES.      

1097
00:48:11,654 --> 00:48:13,287
AND SO IT WOULDN'T              
HAVE BEEN                       

1098
00:48:13,355 --> 00:48:16,490
UNCALLED FOR                    
FOR DIAB TO REQUEST             

1099
00:48:16,559 --> 00:48:20,728
A PARTICULAR TYPE OF PORTRAIT   
FROM GIBRAN.                    

1100
00:48:20,796 --> 00:48:22,663
            YEAH, CERTAINLY NOT.

1101
00:48:22,732 --> 00:48:25,365
        IT'S TYPICAL FOR PEOPLE 
        WHO COMMISSION PORTRAITS

1102
00:48:25,434 --> 00:48:30,070
          TO GUIDE THE ARTIST   
          ON HOW THEY WOULD LIKE

1103
00:48:30,139 --> 00:48:32,506
                FOR THE PORTRAIT
                TO BE PAINTED.  

1104
00:48:32,575 --> 00:48:35,709
  <i> DOES BOB HAVE A PREVIOUSLY</i>   
       <i> UNKNOWN PAINTING</i>        

1105
00:48:35,778 --> 00:48:38,412
           <i> FROM THE</i>            
   <i> "TEMPLE OF ART" SERIES?</i>     

1106
00:48:38,481 --> 00:48:42,149
 <i> TANIA SUGGESTS THAT IF DIAB</i>   
  <i> HAD COMMISSIONED THE WORK,</i>   

1107
00:48:42,218 --> 00:48:45,219
 <i> GIBRAN MAY HAVE MENTIONED IT</i>  
    <i> IN HIS CORRESPONDENCE</i>      

1108
00:48:45,287 --> 00:48:47,254
       <i> WITH HIS LOVER,</i>         
        <i> MARY HASKELL.</i>          

1109
00:48:47,323 --> 00:48:49,156
          LET ME SEE            
    IF I CAN FIND ANYTHING      

1110
00:48:49,225 --> 00:48:51,592
           ABOUT THE            
     "TEMPLE OF ART" HERE.      

1111
00:48:51,660 --> 00:48:53,861
     <i> THERE ARE REFERENCES</i>      
  <i> TO MANY OF THE LUMINARIES</i>    

1112
00:48:53,929 --> 00:48:55,729
       <i> THAT GIBRAN DREW</i>        
         <i> OR PAINTED,</i>           

1113
00:48:55,798 --> 00:48:58,398
  <i> INCLUDING PSYCHOTHERAPIST</i>    
          <i> CARL JUNG,</i>           

1114
00:48:58,467 --> 00:49:00,968
          <i> IRISH POET</i>           
    <i> WILLIAM BUTLER YEATS,</i>      

1115
00:49:01,036 --> 00:49:03,971
  <i> AND THE LEGENDARY ACTRESS</i>    
       <i> SARAH BERNHARDT.</i>        

1116
00:49:04,039 --> 00:49:05,272
        LISTEN TO THIS:         

1117
00:49:05,341 --> 00:49:08,742
     "AT LAST, THE DIVINE       
       SARAH IS CAUGHT."        

1118
00:49:08,811 --> 00:49:11,645
      THIS IS A REFERENCE       
      TO SARAH BERNHARDT.       

1119
00:49:11,714 --> 00:49:14,248
      "BUT IF I AM TO GO        
   THROUGH THE SAME PROCESS     

1120
00:49:14,316 --> 00:49:16,650
     "WITH OTHER GREAT MEN      
          AND WOMEN,            

1121
00:49:16,719 --> 00:49:20,020
 "I MIGHT AS WELL GIVE UP ART   
    AND BECOME A DIPLOMAT."     

1122
00:49:20,089 --> 00:49:23,257
   OKAY, HERE IS A REFERENCE    
           TO DIAB.             

1123
00:49:23,325 --> 00:49:25,292
       <i> I'VE DISCOVERED</i>         
        <i> A CURIOUS NOTE</i>         

1124
00:49:25,361 --> 00:49:26,827
   <i> IN THE HASKELL LETTERS.</i>     

1125
00:49:26,896 --> 00:49:29,596
    <i> I THINK I FINALLY HAVE</i>     
    <i> SOME ANSWERS FOR BOB.</i>      

1126
00:49:29,665 --> 00:49:32,599
BOB, THIS INVESTIGATION         
HAS ALLOWED US                  

1127
00:49:32,668 --> 00:49:35,636
TO GAIN SOME INSIGHT            
OF THE RELATIONSHIP             

1128
00:49:35,704 --> 00:49:39,006
BETWEEN YOUR GRANDFATHER        
AND KHALIL GIBRAN.              

1129
00:49:39,074 --> 00:49:42,809
I SPOKE TO AN EXPERT            
ON HIS ARTWORK,                 

1130
00:49:42,878 --> 00:49:46,313
AND SHE IS OF THE OPINION       
THAT THIS PAINTING              

1131
00:49:46,382 --> 00:49:49,950
IS NOT THE WORK                 
OF KHALIL GIBRAN.               

1132
00:49:50,019 --> 00:49:52,786
       <i> I EXPLAIN TO BOB</i>        
    <i> THAT TO MAKE CERTAIN,</i>      

1133
00:49:52,855 --> 00:49:56,256
   <i> I CONSULTED THE LETTERS</i>     
 <i> AND DIARIES OF MARY HASKELL.</i>  

1134
00:49:56,325 --> 00:49:59,126
AND IT IS THAT SEARCH           
WHICH LED ME                    

1135
00:49:59,194 --> 00:50:02,329
TO ONE OF MY MOST               
IMPORTANT DISCOVERIES.          

1136
00:50:02,398 --> 00:50:04,531
   OKAY, HERE IS A REFERENCE    
           TO DIAB.             

1137
00:50:04,600 --> 00:50:06,867
     IT'S QUITE POLITICAL,      
     AND THIS IS REFERRING      

1138
00:50:06,936 --> 00:50:09,703
       TO THE 1913 PARIS        
          CONFERENCE.           

1139
00:50:09,772 --> 00:50:12,940
  "DIAB AND MYSELF WERE ASKED   
   TO GO AS REPRESENTATIVES.    

1140
00:50:13,008 --> 00:50:16,410
      "THE IDEA IS FINE,        
 BUT AFTER TALKING THINGS OVER  

1141
00:50:16,478 --> 00:50:18,545
       "WITH A COMMITTEE        
          OF SYRIANS,           

1142
00:50:18,614 --> 00:50:21,815
       "I FOUND THAT WE         
  DO NOT AGREE ON ANY POINT.    

1143
00:50:21,884 --> 00:50:26,219
   "DIAB THINKS I AM MAD --     
    OTHERS THINK SO, TOO."      

1144
00:50:26,288 --> 00:50:28,922
     IT HAS NOTHING TO SAY      
   ABOUT HIM DOING A SKETCH     

1145
00:50:28,991 --> 00:50:30,891
    OR A PORTRAIT OF DIAB.      

1146
00:50:30,960 --> 00:50:33,727
    <i> I TELL BOB THAT GIBRAN</i>     
    <i> HAD REFUSED TO ATTEND</i>      

1147
00:50:33,796 --> 00:50:36,730
  <i> THE 1913 PARIS CONFERENCE</i>    
        <i> BECAUSE HE HAD</i>         

1148
00:50:36,799 --> 00:50:39,232
   <i> FUNDAMENTAL DIFFERENCES</i>     
    <i> WITH OTHER ATTENDEES,</i>      

1149
00:50:39,301 --> 00:50:41,601
    <i> INCLUDING NAJEEB DIAB.</i>     

1150
00:50:41,670 --> 00:50:43,270
     <i> SO IT SEEMS UNLIKELY</i>      

1151
00:50:43,339 --> 00:50:45,105
      <i> THAT GIBRAN WOULD</i>        
       <i> PAINT A PORTRAIT</i>        

1152
00:50:45,174 --> 00:50:47,107
       <i> IN COMMEMORATION</i>        
        <i> OF THE EVENT.</i>          

1153
00:50:47,176 --> 00:50:50,944
THE RELATIONSHIP BETWEEN        
YOUR GRANDFATHER                

1154
00:50:51,013 --> 00:50:55,415
AND KHALIL GIBRAN               
WAS NOT ONLY OVER ISSUES        

1155
00:50:55,484 --> 00:50:57,451
OF WRITING AND ART,             

1156
00:50:57,519 --> 00:51:00,821
IT WENT TO THE HEART            
OF THEIR POLITICAL COMMITMENT   

1157
00:51:00,889 --> 00:51:03,190
AND WAS A REFLECTION            

1158
00:51:03,258 --> 00:51:07,294
ON THE EARLY ARAB-AMERICAN      
POLITICAL LEADERSHIP            

1159
00:51:07,363 --> 00:51:09,429
IN THIS COUNTRY.                

1160
00:51:09,498 --> 00:51:11,465
         IT'S QUITE INTERESTING.

1161
00:51:11,533 --> 00:51:14,768
     I NEVER REALIZED THAT      
     THEY WERE EVEN IN POLITICS,

1162
00:51:14,837 --> 00:51:17,604
               MY GRANDFATHER   
               OR KHALIL GIBRAN.

1163
00:51:17,673 --> 00:51:20,040
       IT'S THE ONLY PICTURE    
       I HAVE OF MY GRANDFATHER,

1164
00:51:20,109 --> 00:51:23,443
         AND I'LL STILL KEEP IT 
         AND CHERISH IT AT HOME.

1165
00:51:23,512 --> 00:51:25,579
                    I THANK YOU.

1166
00:51:25,647 --> 00:51:29,416
        <i> IN THE 1960s,</i>          
<i> A GENERATION HUNGRY FOR CHANGE</i> 

1167
00:51:29,485 --> 00:51:32,886
        <i> WAS CAPTIVATED</i>         
<i> BY PASSAGES FROM</i> THE PROPHET,  

1168
00:51:32,955 --> 00:51:36,990
   <i> LIKE "LOVE POSSESSES NOT</i>    
  <i> NOR WOULD IT BE POSSESSED;</i>   

1169
00:51:37,059 --> 00:51:40,394
    <i> FOR LOVE IS SUFFICIENT</i>     
         <i> UNTO LOVE."</i>           

1170
00:51:40,462 --> 00:51:43,663
<i> IN THEIR SEARCH FOR A DIFFERENT</i>
 <i> WAY OF THINKING AND LIVING,</i>   

1171
00:51:43,732 --> 00:51:46,500
  <i> MANY YOUNG, DISILLUSIONED</i>    
          <i> AMERICANS</i>            

1172
00:51:46,568 --> 00:51:49,369
   <i> TURNED TO THE TEACHINGS</i>     
         <i> OF THE EAST.</i>          

1173
00:51:49,438 --> 00:51:51,838
     <i> THE IDEAS EXPRESSED</i>       
        <i> IN</i> THE PROPHET         

1174
00:51:51,907 --> 00:51:55,408
  <i> MIRRORED THEIR STRUGGLE OF</i>   
<i> THE SPIRIT AGAINST MATERIALISM.</i>

1175
00:51:55,477 --> 00:51:57,744
        <i> KHALIL GIBRAN</i>          
        <i> BECAME A VOICE</i>         

1176
00:51:57,813 --> 00:51:59,813
           <i> FOR THE</i>             
   <i> COUNTERCULTURE MOVEMENT.</i>    

1177
00:51:59,882 --> 00:52:01,515
          <i> BUT GIBRAN</i>           
         <i> NEVER LIVED</i>           

1178
00:52:01,583 --> 00:52:04,451
   <i> TO SEE HIS WORDS INSPIRE</i>    
<i> THAT GENERATION OF AMERICANS.</i>  

1179
00:52:04,520 --> 00:52:06,586
     <i> HE DIED OF CIRRHOSIS</i>      
         <i> OF THE LIVER</i>          

1180
00:52:06,655 --> 00:52:09,289
       <i> FROM ALCOHOLISM</i>         
           <i> IN 1931.</i>            

1181
00:52:12,427 --> 00:52:14,461
And so, my fellow Americans...  

1182
00:52:14,530 --> 00:52:16,563
            Elyse:              
     PRESIDENT KENNEDY IS       
 BELIEVED TO HAVE PARAPHRASED   

1183
00:52:16,632 --> 00:52:18,865
    KHALIL GIBRAN'S WRITING     
         WHEN HE SAID:          

1184
00:52:18,934 --> 00:52:23,537
       Ask not what your country
       can do for you,          

1185
00:52:23,605 --> 00:52:26,873
             ask what you can do
             for your country.  

1186
00:52:26,942 --> 00:52:28,575
   [ cheering and applause ]    

1187
00:52:28,644 --> 00:52:31,511
       JFK WAS ALSO FOND        
 OF QUOTING FROM ROBERT FROST   

1188
00:52:31,580 --> 00:52:34,414
  AND EVEN HAD THE POET READ    
     AT HIS INAUGURATION.       

1189
00:52:34,483 --> 00:52:36,983
     IT'S RARE THAT POETRY      
       AND POLITICS MIX,        

1190
00:52:37,052 --> 00:52:40,187
     BUT SOMETIMES TRAGEDY      
   BRINGS THE TWO TOGETHER.     

1191
00:52:40,255 --> 00:52:42,289
    FOLLOWING THE DISASTER      
    THAT CLAIMED THE LIVES      

1192
00:52:42,357 --> 00:52:44,891
  OF SEVEN ASTRONAUTS ABOARD    
 THE SPACE SHUTTLE<i> CHALLENGER</i>   

1193
00:52:44,960 --> 00:52:49,462
  ON JANUARY 28, 1986, RONALD   
 REAGAN ADDRESSED THE NATION.   

1194
00:52:49,531 --> 00:52:50,830
We will never forget them.      

1195
00:52:50,899 --> 00:52:53,066
   WHEN HE ENDED HIS REMARKS    
BY SAYING THE ASTRONAUTS HAD... 

1196
00:52:53,135 --> 00:52:57,704
Slipped the surly bonds of      
Earth to touch the face of God. 

1197
00:52:57,773 --> 00:53:00,173
       HE WAS BORROWING         
 FROM THE FIRST AND LAST LINE   

1198
00:53:00,242 --> 00:53:01,341
       OF "HIGH FLIGHT."        

1199
00:53:01,410 --> 00:53:03,810
     THE POEM WAS WRITTEN       
            IN 1941             

1200
00:53:03,879 --> 00:53:05,812
    BY A 19-YEAR-OLD PILOT      
           OFFICER,             

1201
00:53:05,881 --> 00:53:07,881
  JOHN GILLESPIE MAGEE, JR.,    

1202
00:53:07,950 --> 00:53:09,983
    ON THE BACK OF A LETTER     
         TO HIS MOTHER          

1203
00:53:10,052 --> 00:53:12,652
       JUST A FEW MONTHS        
     BEFORE HE WAS KILLED.      

1204
00:53:12,721 --> 00:53:15,055
 WHEN MARTIN LUTHER KING, JR.,  
       WAS ASSASSINATED,        

1205
00:53:15,123 --> 00:53:17,757
    BOBBY KENNEDY WENT BACK     
          2,500 YEARS           

1206
00:53:17,826 --> 00:53:19,960
       TO THE GREEK POET        
           AESCHYLUS            

1207
00:53:20,028 --> 00:53:22,529
         TO GIVE VOICE          
  TO HIS HOPE FOR THE FUTURE.   

1208
00:53:22,598 --> 00:53:26,900
           Kennedy:             
      Even in our sleep,        
   pain which cannot forget     

1209
00:53:26,969 --> 00:53:31,004
      falls drop by drop        
        upon the heart          

1210
00:53:31,073 --> 00:53:35,075
   until in our own despair,    
       against our will,        

1211
00:53:35,143 --> 00:53:40,280
         comes wisdom           
through the awful grace of God. 

